insert into public.am_questions
  (realm_id,realm_name,level_min,level_max,question,options,correct_idx,knowledge_type,explanation,insight,image_search,tags)
values

-- REALM 1: ANCIENT CIVILIZATIONS (10 questions)
(1,'Ancient Civilizations',1,5,
'What was the ancient Egyptians own name for their homeland?',
'["Kemet, The Black Land","Aegyptos, Land of the Gods","Pharaon, Kingdom of the Sun","Deshret, The Red Desert"]',
0,'historical',
'The ancient Egyptians called their land Kemet, The Black Land, referring to the fertile dark silt deposited by the Nile floods. The name Egypt comes from the Greek Aegyptos, derived from the Egyptian Hwt-Ka-Ptah. Kemet was contrasted with Deshret, the barren Red Land of the desert, a duality that permeated all Egyptian cosmology.',
'The black fertile land and red desert were not just geography, they were a cosmic map. Osiris ruled Kemet, Set ruled Deshret. All Egyptian metaphysics emerged from this primal tension between life and death, order and chaos.',
'ancient egypt nile kemet black land hieroglyphs',ARRAY['egypt','names','history','kemet']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',1,5,
'Why is Gobekli Tepe in Turkey considered one of the most significant archaeological discoveries?',
'["It predates agriculture by 6000+ years proving organised religion preceded farming","It is the largest known ancient city with over 100000 inhabitants","It contains the oldest written language predating Sumerian by 3000 years","It proves ancient Egyptians had a global empire reaching Anatolia"]',
0,'empirical',
'Gobekli Tepe contains massive carved stone pillars assembled into ritual circles dating to 9500-8000 BCE, roughly 6000 years before Stonehenge and before the invention of agriculture. This overturned the long-held theory that organised religion and monument-building emerged only after settled farming.',
'Gobekli Tepe suggests that the human impulse toward the sacred may have preceded and even motivated the agricultural revolution. Hunters and gatherers built temples before they built granaries.',
'Gobekli Tepe Turkey ancient stone circle neolithic',ARRAY['turkey','neolithic','religion','archaeology']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',4,15,
'The Dogon people of Mali are remarkable in esoteric circles for their traditional knowledge about which star system?',
'["Sirius B, an invisible companion star they described before its telescopic confirmation","Orion Belt, which they claimed contained the throne of their creator god","Aldebaran, used to predict floods thousands of years before the Nile calendar","Polaris, tracked through a 26000-year precession cycle"]',
0,'speculative',
'The Dogon reportedly possessed detailed knowledge of Sirius B, a white dwarf companion star invisible to the naked eye, long before its photographic confirmation in 1970. They described its 50-year orbital period and extraordinary density. Whether this came from ancient contact, sophisticated observation, or later transmission remains genuinely debated.',
'This case sits precisely at the boundary between empirical astronomy and esoteric transmission. Whatever its ultimate source, the Dogon material forces a genuine question: how much astronomical knowledge existed in pre-technological societies that we have never properly investigated?',
'Dogon Mali Africa star astronomy Sirius',ARRAY['dogon','sirius','africa','astronomy']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',4,15,
'The Antikythera Mechanism recovered from an ancient Greek shipwreck is remarkable because it is:',
'["An analog computer with 30+ gears that tracked celestial cycles with extraordinary precision","The earliest known navigational compass predating the Chinese version by 500 years","The first mechanical clock capable of tracking time to the second","A surgical device demonstrating advanced ancient Greek medicine"]',
0,'empirical',
'Dating to approximately 100-150 BCE the Antikythera Mechanism contains at least 30 interlocking bronze gears that predicted solar and lunar eclipses tracked the five known planets and calculated the Olympic Games cycle. Its technological sophistication was not matched again until 14th-century astronomical clocks.',
'The Mechanism forces a profound question: if this level of precision existed in 150 BCE what other sophisticated technologies existed in the ancient world and simply did not survive? Its existence suggests ancient technological development was punctuated, with peaks of sophistication that were lost and had to be rediscovered.',
'Antikythera mechanism ancient greek bronze gears astronomy',ARRAY['greece','technology','astronomy','antikythera']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',4,15,
'The Great Pyramid of Giza contains four narrow shafts pointing outward from the Kings and Queens chambers. What do they appear to align with?',
'["Specific stars including Orions Belt and Sirius as they appeared around 2500 BCE","The four cardinal compass directions with perfect north alignment","Sunrise and sunset positions during the solstices","The positions of planets during a rare 2500-year conjunction"]',
0,'historical',
'Researcher Robert Bauval identified that the Great Pyramids shafts appear to align with specific stars as positioned around 2500 BCE: the southern shafts point toward Orions Belt associated with Osiris and Sirius associated with Isis while northern shafts align with circumpolar stars including Alpha Draconis then the pole star.',
'If intentional the Great Pyramid functions simultaneously as a tomb an astronomical instrument and a mythological statement in stone, encoding the Egyptian understanding that death stellar rebirth and cosmic order are inseparable. The building is a cosmology made physical.',
'Great Pyramid Giza Egypt stars Orion astronomy alignments',ARRAY['egypt','pyramids','astronomy','orion']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',12,50,
'Nabta Playa in the Egyptian Sahara contains what archaeoastronomical feature predating Stonehenge?',
'["Stone circles from 5000 BCE aligned with the summer solstice sunrise and the rising of Orion","The earliest agricultural settlement predating Sumerian farming by 3000 years","The oldest hieroglyphic inscriptions found outside the Nile Valley","A massive underground city that served as the blueprint for early Egyptian civilisation"]',
0,'historical',
'Nabta Playa contains stone circles and stellar alignments dating to approximately 5000 BCE, roughly 1000 years before Stonehenge. These structures appear aligned with the summer solstice sunrise and the rising of Orion. The site was used by prehistoric pastoralists during the African Humid Period when the Sahara supported grassland.',
'Nabta Playa suggests that the astronomical and ritual impulses that culminated in Egyptian civilisation had deep prehistoric roots among nomadic Saharan pastoralists. The astronomers of Nabta Playa may have been ancestors of those who built the pyramids.',
'Nabta Playa desert Egypt ancient stone circle astronomy',ARRAY['egypt','sahara','archaeoastronomy','prehistoric']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',12,50,
'The Mayan Dresden Codex primarily contains:',
'["Sophisticated astronomical tables for Venus cycles solar eclipses and the 260-day sacred calendar","A complete history of Mayan kings from the founding of civilisation to the Spanish conquest","Agricultural planting guides tied to the solar year and rainfall predictions","Prophecies concerning the end of the current world age in 2012"]',
0,'historical',
'The Dresden Codex dated 1200-1250 CE but based on much older sources contains sophisticated astronomical tables, most notably a Venus table tracking the 584-day synodic cycle with accuracy equivalent to modern astronomy as well as eclipse tables and calculations for the 260-day tzolkin sacred calendar.',
'The Venus table in the Dresden Codex tracks Venus cycle with an error of only 2 hours over 481 years. This level of astronomical precision achieved through systematic naked-eye observation speaks to a civilisation that considered the movements of planets a matter of sacred importance, a living cosmos requiring attentive reading.',
'Maya Dresden Codex ancient manuscript astronomy Venus',ARRAY['maya','dresden codex','astronomy','venus']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',1,5,
'The ancient Egyptian concept of Ma at refers to:',
'["Cosmic order truth justice and harmony, the principle governing both the universe and human society","The divine feminine creator goddess who separated earth from sky at the beginning of time","The afterlife realm where souls were judged before proceeding to paradise","Sacred knowledge held exclusively by pharaohs and high priests of Heliopolis"]',
0,'historical',
'Ma at was both a goddess depicted with an ostrich feather and an abstract principle, the cosmic force of truth order balance and justice that permeated all creation. Pharaohs were obligated to uphold Ma at. In the afterlife the deceased heart was weighed against Ma ats feather, if balanced the soul proceeded to paradise.',
'Ma at represents one of the most sophisticated ancient conceptions of cosmic ethics, moral order and physical order are not separate domains but the same principle operating at different scales. When a human lies or acts unjustly they are not merely violating a social contract but disrupting the fabric of cosmic reality.',
'ancient Egypt goddess balance justice cosmic order',ARRAY['egypt','maat','cosmic order','ethics']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',4,15,
'What makes the ancient Indian city of Dwarka off the coast of Gujarat archaeologically significant?',
'["Underwater ruins discovered at 40m depth match the ancient description of the sunken city of Lord Krishna in the Mahabharata","It is the oldest known continuously inhabited city in the world dating to 10000 BCE","It contains the earliest evidence of iron smelting predating the Near Eastern Iron Age by 2000 years","The earliest proto-Sanskrit inscriptions discovered here link Indian and Sumerian writing systems"]',
0,'speculative',
'Marine archaeology surveys led by the National Institute of Ocean Technology beginning in 2000 discovered submerged structures off Dwarka at depths of 30-40 metres including a city grid with stone anchors walls and artifacts tentatively dated to approximately 9000-7500 BCE. Dwarka is described in the Mahabharata as the legendary city of Krishna that sank into the sea.',
'The Dwarka discovery sits in the fascinating territory where mythology and archaeology potentially intersect. If the submerged structures are confirmed as a human settlement from 9000+ BCE it would suggest sophisticated urban planning existed in India at a time when mainstream history assumes only hunter-gatherer societies.',
'Dwarka India underwater ancient ruins ocean archaeology',ARRAY['dwarka','india','underwater archaeology','ancient cities']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',12,50,
'The ancient Sumerian city of Eridu is significant because:',
'["It is considered the oldest city in the world circa 5400 BCE and the mythological birthplace of civilisation in Sumerian tradition","It contains the only known intact Sumerian library with over 30000 clay tablets","It was the first city to develop a writing system, all other scripts derived from Eridus original pictographs","It sits at the geographic centre of the ancient Near East and served as a religious capital for all Mesopotamian cultures"]',
0,'historical',
'Eridu dates to approximately 5400 BCE and is widely considered the worlds oldest city. In Sumerian mythology Eridu was the first city lowered from heaven to earth associated with Enki, the god of wisdom and civilisation. The site contains at least 18 successive temples built upon each other suggesting continuous sacred use over millennia.',
'The Sumerian foundation myth places the origin of civilisation not in agricultural technology but in divine gift, the gods gave humanity the me (divine decrees: writing law music kingship) at Eridu. This origin narrative locates the birth of culture in a vertical transmission from a higher order not a horizontal evolutionary process.',
'ancient Sumer Mesopotamia ruins Iraq archaeology',ARRAY['sumer','eridu','mesopotamia','oldest city']),

-- REALM 2: HERMETIC WISDOM (10 questions)
(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',1,5,
'According to the Kybalion what is the First Hermetic Principle?',
'["Mentalism: The All is Mind the Universe is Mental","Correspondence: As above so below as below so above","Vibration: Nothing rests everything moves everything vibrates","Rhythm: Everything flows out and in everything has its tides"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Principle of Mentalism states that the entire Universe is mental, that The All creates all reality as a thought within infinite consciousness. This does not dismiss physical reality as illusion but declares its fundamental nature is consciousness not matter. It is the master key from which all other Hermetic principles are derived.',
'The Principle of Mentalism finds remarkable resonance in quantum physics where the observer effect suggests consciousness plays a role in collapsing possibility into observable reality. Whether metaphorical or pointing to a deeper truth about the mental nature of the universe remains one of the most fascinating open questions.',
'hermetic wisdom sacred geometry mind universe light',ARRAY['hermeticism','kybalion','mentalism','principles']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',1,5,
'As above so below originates from which foundational Hermetic text?',
'["The Emerald Tablet attributed to Hermes Trismegistus","The Corpus Hermeticum Dialogue I Poemandres","The Kybalion published in 1908 by The Three Initiates","Platos Timaeus describing the relationship of Forms to matter"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The phrase derives from the Emerald Tablet, one of the most influential documents in Western alchemy and esoteric philosophy. The oldest known Arabic version dates to the 6th-8th century CE. The full phrase: "That which is above is like that which is below and that which is below is like that which is above to accomplish the miracles of the one thing."',
'The Emerald Tablet distills the entire Hermetic worldview into a few sentences, macrocosm and microcosm mirror each other the celestial and terrestrial reflect the same principles and understanding one level of reality illuminates all others. This principle has influenced Renaissance alchemy Jungian psychology and modern complexity theory.',
'Emerald Tablet alchemy Hermes ancient gold mystical inscription',ARRAY['hermeticism','emerald tablet','as above so below','alchemy']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',4,15,
'In Hermetic alchemy the Philosophers Stone was primarily understood by serious alchemists as:',
'["Spiritual transformation, the transmutation of the base human soul into gold through enlightenment","A literal physical substance capable of turning lead into gold for material wealth","A secret society membership code used by early Rosicrucians","An ancient meteorite containing unique catalytic properties"]',
0,'esoteric',
'While exoteric alchemy sought to literally transmute base metals into gold esoteric alchemy used the same language metaphorically for spiritual transformation. The Philosophers Stone represented the perfected spiritual state, dissolution of the ego (nigredo) purification (albedo) and emergence of spiritual gold (rubedo). Many serious alchemists understood alchemy primarily as a psychological and spiritual art.',
'Carl Jung devoted decades to alchemical texts concluding that alchemists were unconsciously projecting their psychological processes onto matter. The stages of alchemical transformation map almost perfectly onto his individuation process. The alchemists were doing genuine inner work while believing they were transforming metals.',
'alchemy philosopher stone gold transformation medieval laboratory',ARRAY['alchemy','philosopher stone','transformation','hermetic']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',4,15,
'The Fibonacci sequence converges to which ratio that appears throughout nature and sacred geometry?',
'["The Golden Ratio approximately 1.618","Pi approximately 3.14159","The square root of 2 approximately 1.414","Eulers number approximately 2.718"]',
0,'empirical',
'The Fibonacci sequence converges to the Golden Ratio (phi approximately 1.618033). This ratio appears in the spiral arrangement of sunflower seeds pinecone scales nautilus shells hurricane patterns galaxy spirals and human body proportions. The ancient Greeks considered it the most aesthetically perfect proportion and embedded it in the Parthenon.',
'The omnipresence of the Golden Ratio in natural growth patterns suggests it is not a human construct but a fundamental principle of how matter organises itself. When sacred geometry practitioners place the Golden Ratio at the centre of their cosmology they are pointing at something genuinely remarkable about the mathematical nature of reality.',
'fibonacci golden ratio nautilus shell sacred geometry spiral nature',ARRAY['fibonacci','golden ratio','sacred geometry','mathematics']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',4,15,
'The Hermetic Principle of Polarity states:',
'["Everything has its pair of opposites and opposites are identical in nature differing only in degree","Opposites are fundamentally different substances existing in eternal conflict","Every action produces an equal and opposite reaction anticipating Newtons third law","All creation oscillates between two poles the material and the spiritual"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Principle of Polarity from the Kybalion states that all apparent opposites are the same thing differing only in degree: hot and cold are both temperature light and dark are both illumination love and hate are both feeling. This has profound practical implications, you can transmute one pole into another by moving along the same continuum.',
'The Hermetic Principle of Polarity is both a cosmological statement and a practical psycho-spiritual tool. If all opposites exist on the same continuum then no negative state is permanent or absolute, it is always possible to raise the vibration toward the positive pole.',
'hermetic polarity yin yang opposites balance sacred',ARRAY['hermeticism','polarity','opposites','kybalion']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',12,50,
'What does the Corpus Hermeticum Poemandres reveal about the nature of the human mind and its relationship to the divine?',
'["Individual human minds are divine sparks of the Alls infinite mind that descended into matter and can return through gnosis","The human mind was created by the Demiurge as an imperfect copy of the divine mind and cannot return to the source","Mind is a universal substance distinct from both matter and spirit, the third element of the Hermetic trinity","Human minds are temporary configurations of universal mental substance that dissolve back into it at death"]',
0,'esoteric',
'In the Poemandres the divine Mind reveals to Hermes that individual human minds are essentially of the same nature as the All, divine sparks that have descended into the material world through the seven planetary spheres acquiring ego and passions at each level. The path of return involves recognising ones true divine nature through gnosis.',
'The Hermetic vision of the human mind as a localised expression of the infinite divine Mind is one of the most radical affirmations of human dignity in any tradition. It does not say humans are fallen creatures needing external salvation, it says they are divine beings who have temporarily forgotten their nature.',
'Corpus Hermeticum ancient manuscript Hermes divine wisdom philosophy',ARRAY['corpus hermeticum','poemandres','divine mind','gnosis']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',12,50,
'The seven Hermetic principles of the Kybalion correspond in remarkable ways to which modern scientific framework?',
'["Quantum field theory and systems theory where Mentalism parallels information primacy Vibration parallels quantum fields and Correspondence mirrors scale invariance","Classical Newtonian mechanics where each principle maps to one of Newtons laws","Darwinian evolutionary theory where the principles describe stages in the evolution of consciousness","General relativity where the principles describe how spacetime curves in the presence of mental energy"]',
0,'philosophical',
'The correspondences are striking: Mentalism parallels information-theoretic views of physics and quantum mechanics measurement problem. Vibration maps to quantum field concepts. Correspondence mirrors scale invariance and fractal self-similarity. Polarity echoes quantum superposition. The Kybalion was published in 1908, the same year as Einsteins first quantum paper.',
'The parallel development of Hermetic philosophy and quantum physics in the early 20th century without documented mutual influence is itself a kind of synchronicity. It suggests both may be reaching through very different methods toward the same underlying structure of reality.',
'hermetic principles sacred geometry quantum physics science',ARRAY['kybalion','seven principles','quantum physics','hermetic']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',1,5,
'Mystery Schools of the ancient world shared what core practice?',
'["Initiatory experiences designed to produce direct experiential knowledge of death and rebirth before physical death","Public theatrical performances of mythological stories for mass spiritual education","Competitive examinations of philosophical knowledge to identify suitable philosopher-kings","Secret mathematical research programmes funded by city-states for astronomical purposes"]',
0,'historical',
'Mystery Schools provided initiatory experiences, often involving fasting ritual darkness symbolic death and rebirth, designed to give initiates direct experiential knowledge. The Eleusinian Mysteries lasted nearly 2000 years and were considered the greatest spiritual institution of the ancient Mediterranean world. Many Greek philosophers including Plato and Aristotle were initiates.',
'The Mystery Schools understood something that modern religious education often forgets: there is a fundamental difference between information about spiritual reality and direct experience of it. Knowing that consciousness is immortal is categorically different from experiencing ones own consciousness surviving a symbolic death.',
'ancient Greece mystery school initiation Eleusis sacred ritual',ARRAY['mystery schools','eleusis','initiation','ancient greece','gnosis']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',4,15,
'Paracelsus the Renaissance alchemist and physician revolutionised medicine by:',
'["Introducing chemistry-based treatments and the idea that specific remedies target specific diseases, the foundation of pharmaceutical medicine","Discovering that all disease originates in the astral body and must be treated through spiritual means first","Proving that the four humours were alchemical substances requiring transmutation","Developing the first systematic surgical techniques based on Hermetic principles"]',
0,'historical',
'Paracelsus (1493-1541) rejected Galenic humoral medicine and introduced specific remedies for specific diseases using minerals metals and chemical compounds. He introduced laudanum mercury treatments for syphilis and the doctrine of signatures. He is considered one of the founders of modern pharmacology and toxicology.',
'Paracelsus demonstrates the productive tension within alchemy: his spiritual worldview actually led him to practical medical innovations. His belief that understanding cosmic correspondences would reveal remedies was a flawed premise that nonetheless generated genuinely useful results, how esoteric frameworks can produce empirical discoveries.',
'Paracelsus alchemy medieval medicine pharmacy Renaissance',ARRAY['paracelsus','alchemy','medicine','renaissance']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',12,50,
'What is the Hermetic concept of the Three Parts of the Wisdom of the Whole Universe attributed to Hermes Trismegistus?',
'["The three-part wisdom encompasses the operation of the sun (theurgy) the operation of the stars (astrology) and the operation of nature (alchemy)","The three parts are mind (nous) word (logos) and life (zoe), the three divine emanations from which all creation proceeds","The three parts are birth existence and return, the three phases of every cosmic cycle from aeon to aeon","The three parts are fire water and earth, the three primordial elements from which all matter is composed"]',
0,'esoteric',
'Hermes Trismegistus (Thrice-Great Hermes) derives his title from being master of three arts: theurgy (divine magic and religious ritual) astrology (the science of celestial influences) and alchemy (the art of transformation). These three constitute the complete Hermetic science, understanding the divine forces (theurgy) their patterns of influence (astrology) and their application in transformation (alchemy).',
'The three-part mastery of Hermes Trismegistus maps onto the three fundamental Hermetic operations: knowing the patterns of correspondence (astronomy/astrology) working with them practically (alchemy) and aligning oneself with their divine source (theurgy). Together they constitute what the Hermeticists called the complete science, the unified understanding of how the cosmos works at all three levels.',
'Hermes Trismegistus thrice great ancient wisdom philosophy',ARRAY['hermes trismegistus','three parts','hermetic science','theurgy']),

-- REALM 3: GNOSTICISM (10 questions)
(3,'Gnosticism',1,5,
'In Gnostic cosmology the Demiurge is best described as:',
'["A lesser flawed creator god who fashioned the material world while mistaking himself for the supreme deity","The highest divine being, the Gnostic name for the God of Abraham","The divine feminine principle that descended into matter to animate creation","An evil cosmic force equivalent to Satan in Christian orthodoxy"]',
0,'philosophical',
'The Demiurge in Gnostic thought is the creator of the material world, but crucially not the highest God. Typically portrayed as an ignorant or arrogant lesser deity who created the imperfect material realm and falsely believes himself supreme many Gnostic systems identified the Demiurge with the God of the Old Testament. The true supreme God transcends material creation entirely.',
'The Gnostic Demiurge solves a profound theological problem: if there is an all-good all-powerful supreme deity why is the world full of suffering? The Gnostic answer: the supreme deity did not create this world. A lesser flawed being did. This frames existence not as a divine punishment but as an imperfect creation from which liberation is genuinely possible.',
'Gnostic cosmology light darkness divine emanation ancient symbols',ARRAY['gnosticism','demiurge','cosmology','creator']),

(3,'Gnosticism',1,5,
'The Nag Hammadi Library discovered in 1945 in Egypt is historically significant because it contains:',
'["52 mostly Gnostic texts including the Gospel of Thomas, primary sources of Gnostic Christianity buried around 390 CE","The oldest known complete Hebrew Bible predating the Dead Sea Scrolls by 400 years","The lost writings of Plato including a complete version of the Timaeus","Ancient Egyptian magical papyri proving the existence of Hermetic mystery schools"]',
0,'historical',
'The Nag Hammadi Library is a collection of 52 mostly Gnostic texts discovered in a sealed earthenware jar near Nag Hammadi Egypt. They were likely buried around 390 CE to protect them from early Church authorities who condemned Gnosticism as heresy. The most famous text is the Gospel of Thomas, 114 sayings attributed to Jesus with no narrative context.',
'The Nag Hammadi discovery dramatically changed our understanding of early Christianity revealing that Christian diversity in the 2nd-3rd centuries was far greater than orthodox tradition acknowledges. Gnostic Christians were not a bizarre fringe, they were sophisticated theological communities with a radically different cosmological lens.',
'Nag Hammadi Egypt ancient scrolls Gnostic discovery library',ARRAY['nag hammadi','gnosticism','early christianity','gospel of thomas']),

(3,'Gnosticism',4,15,
'Who is Sophia in Gnostic mythology and what is her central dramatic role?',
'["The divine feminine aeon whose desire to know the Father without her consort caused her to fall into matter generating the Demiurge and the material world","A mortal woman who achieved gnosis and became the first human to escape the material realm","The consort of the Demiurge who attempts to limit his power over human souls","A Gnostic name for Mary Magdalene who preserved Jesus secret teachings after the Crucifixion"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Sophia (Greek: wisdom) is a divine feminine aeon dwelling in the Pleroma. In her desire to know or emanate the ineffable Father without her divine consort she generates a formless incomplete being, which becomes the Demiurge the creator of the material world. Sophia herself partially falls into matter in grief and her rescue and restoration is central to the Gnostic cosmic drama.',
'Sophias myth encodes a profound psychological truth: the desire to grasp what transcends conceptual understanding generates a kind of exile from wholeness. The material world in this telling is not the result of divine intention but of divine yearning, the cosmos is born from wisdoms longing.',
'Sophia wisdom divine feminine light Byzantine sacred art',ARRAY['sophia','wisdom','gnosticism','divine feminine']),

(3,'Gnosticism',4,15,
'What does the Gnostic term Pleroma refer to?',
'["The divine fullness, the realm of perfect divine light and the totality of divine emanations or aeons","The material world considered an imperfect shadow of divine reality","The process of spiritual purification through which humans return to the divine","The Gnostic equivalent of Hell, a realm of dense matter where unenlightened souls are reborn"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Pleroma (Greek: fullness completeness) refers to the divine realm in its totality, where the supreme God (the Monad) and all the divine emanations (aeons) dwell in perfect unity. The Pleroma stands in absolute contrast to the Kenoma, the emptiness or deficiency of the material world. The Gnostic spiritual path involves recognising ones divine spark as belonging to the Pleroma.',
'Pleroma maps onto what mystical traditions call the Absolute, the undifferentiated ground of being from which all manifestation emerges. The Gnostic innovation is to place this in radical contrast to the material world creating a cosmic drama of exile and return that gives ultimate meaning to human spiritual striving.',
'Pleroma divine light sacred emanations Gnostic cosmology',ARRAY['pleroma','gnosticism','divine realm','aeons']),

(3,'Gnosticism',12,50,
'How does the Gospel of Thomas differ from the canonical Gospels in its understanding of the Kingdom of God?',
'["It presents the Kingdom as an inner present reality experienced through self-knowledge rather than a future apocalyptic event","It describes the Kingdom as a physical realm Jesus will establish after his Second Coming","It identifies the Kingdom with the Gnostic Pleroma accessible only to initiated Gnostic Christians","It replaces the concept of the Kingdom with the Hermetic idea of the All"]',
0,'philosophical',
'The Gospel of Thomas (Saying 3): "The Kingdom is inside of you and it is outside of you." Saying 113: "The Kingdom of the Father is spread out upon the earth and men do not see it." This presents enlightenment as a present inner realisation rather than a future cosmic event, completely different from the apocalyptic expectation in the Synoptic Gospels.',
'The contrast between Thomas and the Synoptic Gospels is essentially the contrast between mystical immediacy and apocalyptic expectation. Thomas Jesus is not preparing humanity for an imminent end, he is pointing at what is already and always present. This aligns Thomas with Zen and Advaita Vedanta far more than with mainstream Christianity.',
'Gospel Thomas ancient Coptic papyrus wisdom sayings',ARRAY['gospel of thomas','kingdom of god','gnosis','sayings']),

(3,'Gnosticism',12,50,
'What distinguishes Valentinian Gnosticism from other Gnostic schools?',
'["Its sophisticated 30-aeon Pleroma system and its use of mainstream Christian texts with allegorical Gnostic interpretation making it the most intellectually developed Gnostic school","Its complete rejection of the Old Testament as the work of the Demiurge","Its synthesis of Platonic philosophy with Egyptian mysticism","Its democratic structure treating all initiates equally unlike other Gnostic schools"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Valentinus (c. 100-160 CE) developed the most elaborate Gnostic cosmological system, a Pleroma of 30 aeons arranged in 15 pairs emanating from the supreme Monad, and was the most intellectually sophisticated of the Gnostic teachers. Uniquely Valentinians read and used the canonical Gospels but interpreted them allegorically. Valentinus nearly became Bishop of Rome.',
'The near-election of Valentinus to the papacy is one of historys great what-ifs. Had he become Bishop of Rome Christianity would have developed as a more mystical philosophically sophisticated tradition focused on direct inner experience. The choice of proto-orthodox over Valentinian framework shaped Western civilisation for two millennia.',
'Valentinus Gnostic Pleroma ancient Rome Christianity early church',ARRAY['valentinus','gnosticism','pleroma','early christianity']),

(3,'Gnosticism',12,50,
'The Gnostic concept of the divine spark (pneuma) within humans states that:',
'["Each human contains a fragment of divine light that is foreign to the material world and is destined to return to the Pleroma","The human spirit is a creation of the Demiurge imperfect but capable of improvement through moral effort","Divine consciousness is not present in individuals but only in the collective community of believers","The spark of divinity was placed in humans by the supreme God as a gift but confers no special destiny"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Gnostic anthropology divides humans into three types: hylics (dominated by matter incapable of gnosis) psychics (balanced between matter and spirit capable of faith) and pneumatics (containing the divine spark capable of gnosis and return to the Pleroma). The pneumatics divine spark is not earned, it is inherent though covered by veils of matter and ignorance.',
'The Gnostic doctrine of the pneuma, the divine spark buried in matter foreign to its environment longing to return, is one of the most psychologically resonant teachings in all of religious history. It speaks directly to the experience of feeling fundamentally out of place in the material world of sensing that something within does not belong to ordinary existence.',
'divine spark light consciousness Gnostic emanation cosmos spiritual',ARRAY['divine spark','pneuma','gnosticism','human nature']),

(3,'Gnosticism',4,15,
'What is the Gnostic understanding of salvation or liberation (called gnosis)?',
'["Direct experiential self-knowledge, recognising ones own divine nature as a spark of the supreme God not separated from but identical with it","Moral purification through virtuous living and correct observance of divine commandments","Faith in the redemptive power of Jesus sacrifice on the cross, identical to orthodox Christian soteriology","Accumulation of spiritual merit through prayer fasting and service to others across multiple incarnations"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Gnosis (Greek: knowledge) in the Gnostic context is not intellectual information but direct experiential self-knowledge, the living realisation that ones deepest nature is divine not material. This gnosis is liberating because it dissolves the fundamental misidentification (the ego believing itself to be a material creature) that is the root of spiritual bondage.',
'The distinction between pistis (faith) and gnosis (knowledge) is fundamental: pistis is believing something on authority while gnosis is knowing it directly through experience. Orthodox Christianity built its soteriology on pistis, salvation through faith. Gnosticism built its soteriology on gnosis, liberation through direct self-knowledge. This is the same distinction that separates exoteric religion from mysticism in every tradition.',
'Gnostic knowledge light divine emanation ancient wisdom symbols',ARRAY['gnosis','gnosticism','salvation','knowledge','liberation']),

(3,'Gnosticism',1,5,
'Al-Hallaj the Sufi mystic was executed in 922 CE for declaring:',
'["Ana al-Haqq, I am the Truth or I am the Real, interpreted as claiming to be God","La ilaha illa Allah, There is no God but God, which he reportedly said heretically without the second part","Al-insanu sirru Allah, The human being is the secret of God, considered a blasphemous equation of man with the divine","Al-fana wal-baqa, The annihilation and subsistence, claiming to have permanently dissolved into God"]',
0,'historical',
'Al-Hallaj (858-922 CE) declared Ana al-Haqq, I am the Truth, where al-Haqq (the Truth or the Real) is one of the 99 names of Allah in Islam. Orthodox Islamic authorities interpreted this as claiming personal divinity, blasphemy. Sufis interpreted it as the authentic expression of mystical union where the personal self is annihilated and only God remains as the speaking subject.',
'The theological controversy around Ana al-Haqq reveals the fundamental tension in theistic mysticism: how does the mystics experience of unity with God relate to orthodox doctrine of Gods absolute transcendence? Is the mystic who says I am God committing the ultimate sin of shirk (associating something with God) or expressing the ultimate truth of tawhid (divine unity)? The same experience produces opposite interpretations depending on the theological framework applied.',
'Al-Hallaj Sufi mystic Islam Baghdad ancient manuscript',ARRAY['al-hallaj','sufism','mysticism','islam','fana']),

(3,'Gnosticism',4,15,
'The Gnostic Gospel of Philip uses the term koinonos in relation to Mary Magdalene. What has this caused significant scholarly debate about?',
'["Whether Mary Magdalene held an authoritative apostolic role in early Christianity equal to or exceeding that of the male disciples","Whether the physical resurrection of Jesus was meant to be understood literally or symbolically in Gnostic Christianity","Whether female initiates could receive the highest Gnostic sacraments or were limited to the lower mysteries","Whether the Gnostic understanding of marriage as a sacred sacrament influenced later Christian attitudes toward sexuality"]',
0,'historical',
'The Gospel of Philip (Nag Hammadi) refers to Mary Magdalene as Jesus koinonos, a Greek term variously translated as companion partner or consort, and describes Jesus as loving her more than all the disciples and often kissing her. Scholars debate whether this indicates a uniquely authoritative role for Mary in the Gnostic communities whether it should be read spiritually allegorically or literally and what it reveals about gender in early Christianity.',
'The Mary Magdalene question in Gnostic scholarship reveals how much of early Christianity remains contested. The canonical Gospels marginalize Mary while the Gnostic texts consistently elevate her, in some Gnostic texts she is the apostle to the apostles the one who truly understood Jesus teachings while the male disciples remained confused. This alternative tradition was deliberately suppressed during the formation of the orthodox canon.',
'Mary Magdalene Gnostic early Christianity ancient manuscript wisdom',ARRAY['mary magdalene','gospel of philip','gnosticism','early christianity']),

-- REALM 4: EASTERN TRADITIONS (10 questions)
(4,'Eastern Traditions',1,5,
'What are the Four Noble Truths at the foundation of Buddhist teaching?',
'["Suffering exists suffering has a cause (craving) suffering can end and the Eightfold Path leads to its ending","Life is suffering the self is real but imprisoned karma is inescapable and only monks can be liberated","The body is impure sensations are unsatisfactory mind is impermanent and consciousness is empty","Non-attachment non-violence truthfulness and compassion are the four foundations of liberation"]',
0,'philosophical',
'The Four Noble Truths: 1) Dukkha, suffering pervades conditioned existence. 2) Samudaya, the origin of suffering is craving (tanha) and clinging. 3) Nirodha, cessation of craving leads to nirvana. 4) Magga, the Eightfold Path leads to this cessation. These were the Buddhas first teaching after his enlightenment delivered at Sarnath.',
'What makes the Four Noble Truths radical is locating the cause of suffering not in external circumstances or divine punishment but in the minds own craving and clinging. This makes liberation genuinely possible through inner transformation, a profoundly empowering diagnosis that puts the cause and cure of suffering within human reach.',
'Buddha statue meditation Sarnath India dharma teaching',ARRAY['buddhism','four noble truths','dukkha','dharma']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',1,5,
'The first line of the Tao Te Ching establishes its central teaching by:',
'["Declaring that the Tao which can be named is not the eternal Tao, pointing beyond language to the wordless absolute","Describing the ten thousand things that emerge from the Taos infinite creative power","Comparing the Tao to water the softest substance that overcomes the hardest","Beginning with wu wei the principle of non-action through which all things are accomplished"]',
0,'philosophical',
'The Tao Te Ching opens: "The Tao that can be named is not the eternal Tao." This immediate paradox establishes the entire teaching: the ultimate principle of reality transcends all conceptualisation and language. Any attempt to define or capture it in words already distorts it, yet the text spends 80 chapters using words to point at what transcends words.',
'The opening paradox is structurally identical to the Gnostic apophatic theology of the Monad the Advaita teaching that Brahman is neti neti (not this not this) and the Zen masters refusal to define enlightenment. All genuine mystical traditions begin with the same insight: the ultimate reality is wordless and all teachings about it are fingers pointing at the moon.',
'Tao Te Ching ancient Chinese philosophy scroll Laozi',ARRAY['taoism','tao te ching','laozi','wu wei']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',4,15,
'Advaita Vedantas teaching Atman is Brahman (tat tvam asi) means:',
'["The individual self is identical with ultimate reality, there is only one consciousness appearing as multiplicity through maya","The individual soul is separate from God but can merge with him through devotion and surrender","Individual consciousness is an illusion and only Brahman the universal body is ultimately real","The self must transcend itself through spiritual practice to become God as a new higher state"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Advaita (non-dual) Vedanta taught by Adi Shankaracharya in the 8th century CE states that Atman and Brahman are not merely similar or connected, they are identical. The appearance of multiplicity and separateness is maya (misperceived as ultimately real). Liberation (moksha) is the direct recognition of this non-dual nature, not achieving something new but removing the misunderstanding that obscures what was always true.',
'The equation Atman equals Brahman is the most radical non-dualism in the worlds philosophical traditions. It does not say God is great and humans are lesser. It says the consciousness looking out of your eyes is the same consciousness that is the universe. There are not two consciousnesses, just one.',
'Hindu temple Vedanta India sacred ancient philosophy',ARRAY['vedanta','advaita','atman','brahman','non-duality']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',4,15,
'In yogic and tantric traditions kundalini energy is described as:',
'["A coiled serpent energy at the base of the spine that rises through chakras toward the crown producing spiritual awakening","The universal life force (prana) that flows through all living things cultivated through breathing","A state of deep meditation where individual consciousness merges temporarily with universal consciousness","The sacred feminine aspect of God (Shakti) that must be reunited with the masculine (Shiva) through celibacy"]',
0,'esoteric',
'Kundalini (Sanskrit: coiled one) is described in tantric traditions as a dormant spiritual energy coiled at the base of the spine. Through specific practices it can be awakened and guided upward through the seven chakras along the sushumna nadi to the crown chakra producing samadhi. Contemporary researchers like Stanislav Grof have documented powerful psychological phenomena associated with kundalini awakening.',
'The kundalini model is one of the most detailed maps of the human energy body ever developed. Whether understood literally as a bioelectric force or metaphorically as a description of psychological transformation it has proven useful for practitioners across 2000+ years. The specificity of the chakra system allows for a form of inner diagnostics that Western psychology is only beginning to develop parallels for.',
'kundalini yoga chakra spine energy meditation India awakening',ARRAY['kundalini','chakras','yoga','tantra','energy']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',12,50,
'What is the fundamental difference between Advaita Vedanta and Kashmir Shaivism?',
'["Advaita sees the world as maya or superimposed illusion while Kashmir Shaivism sees the world as Shivas real divine play or lila","Advaita affirms a personal God while Kashmir Shaivism denies any personal aspect of the absolute","Advaita requires renunciation while Kashmir Shaivism permits householder engagement with the world","They are essentially identical, both emerged from the same 8th-century Shankaracharya commentaries"]',
0,'philosophical',
'While both are non-dual they differ profoundly on the status of the manifest world. Advaita Vedanta teaches that Brahman alone is real and the world of multiplicity is superimposed through maya, it must ultimately be transcended. Kashmir Shaivism (especially Abhinavaguptas Trika system) teaches that the world is the real expression of Shivas divine consciousness, not illusion to be negated but divine play.',
'Kashmir Shaivisms view that everything is Shiva playing hide-and-seek with himself is perhaps the most joyful and world-affirming form of non-dualism ever developed. Unlike Advaiatas path of renunciation Kashmir Shaivism allows for full engagement with life sensation and creativity as expressions of divine consciousness.',
'Kashmir Shaivism Shiva temple India ancient philosophy',ARRAY['kashmir shaivism','advaita','shiva','non-duality']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',12,50,
'What is the Zen koan designed to accomplish?',
'["Exhaust the conceptual mind so that direct awakening (satori) can occur in the space beyond rational thought","Test whether a student has memorised the correct answer from oral transmission","Teach students to think creatively and laterally outside conventional frameworks","Demonstrate that sound is a mental construction with no inherent external reality"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Zen koans are paradoxical questions specifically designed to frustrate and exhaust the conceptual discriminating mind. The mind that operates through categories logic and language cannot solve the koan because the koan has no conceptual solution. When the student wrestles with it intensely enough and the thinking mind finally collapses in exhaustion direct awareness becomes apparent, this is satori.',
'The koan system represents one of the most sophisticated pedagogical technologies ever developed for the specific purpose of inducing awakening. Unlike gradual path traditions the koan tradition suggests awakening can occur suddenly when the right conditions are met. The sharpest and most confused students can have the same koan, the difference is not intelligence but the depth of inquiry.',
'Zen Buddhism Japan meditation koan temple monk garden',ARRAY['zen','koan','satori','awakening','buddhism']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',4,15,
'The Buddhist concept of anatman (non-self) teaches that:',
'["There is no permanent unchanging self, the sense of I is a constantly changing stream of experiences with no fixed essence","The self is real but must be transcended through spiritual practice to achieve liberation","Individual consciousness is an illusion created by karma, only the cosmic Brahman is truly real","The self continues after death as an unchanging soul that reincarnates until enlightenment"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Anatman (Sanskrit: no-self; Pali: anatta) is one of Buddhism''s three marks of existence. The Buddha taught that what we call the self is not a fixed entity but a flowing stream of five constantly changing aggregates (skandhas): form sensation perception mental formations and consciousness. There is no unchanging soul behind these, the sense of a permanent self is a cognitive error that generates clinging and suffering.',
'The doctrine of anatman is simultaneously the most counter-intuitive and the most liberating Buddhist teaching. Counter-intuitive because our entire social and psychological structure is built around the reality of the self. Liberating because if the self is not a fixed thing but a process then change is inevitable, and the suffering caused by clinging to a permanent self dissolves when the self is seen as a process rather than a thing.',
'Buddhist meditation no self Zen temple Japan mindfulness',ARRAY['anatman','anatta','non-self','buddhism','skandhas']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',4,15,
'The Taoist concept of wu wei (non-action) teaches:',
'["Acting in alignment with the natural flow of reality rather than forcing, effortless action that achieves without struggle","Complete passivity and inaction, the sage does nothing because all action creates karma","The renunciation of all goals and desires, achievement is impossible without surrendering the desire to achieve","Acting only through the body not through the mind, all mental interference with natural impulse is wu weis opposite"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Wu wei does not mean inaction or laziness, it means action so naturally aligned with the Tao that it requires no force produces no resistance and leaves no trace. The metaphors used, water carving the Grand Canyon a skilled craftsman whose tool moves as if by itself, all point to effortless effectiveness through perfect alignment with conditions.',
'Wu weis paradox is that the most effective action is often the action that feels like non-action, so perfectly aligned with conditions that it seems effortless. This maps onto the psychological experience of flow in which peak performance occurs precisely when the effortful self steps aside. The Taoist sage and the master athlete are engaged in the same fundamental discipline.',
'Tao Te Ching Taoist philosophy water flow nature wisdom',ARRAY['taoism','wu wei','non-action','effortless','flow']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',1,5,
'In Hindu tradition what is the concept of maya?',
'["The power of illusion or mismeasurement that causes the one infinite reality to appear as many separate things, not that the world is unreal but that its separateness is misperceived","The goddess of illusion who spins the web of material existence to trap souls for the purpose of their education","The cycle of rebirth through which souls accumulate karma until they achieve liberation","The divine creative play through which Brahman creates the universe for its own enjoyment, equivalent to the Shaiva concept of lila"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Maya in Advaita Vedanta is the cosmic power of mismeasurement or superimposition, the cognitive error that makes the one infinite Brahman appear as many separate things. It is not that the world is nonexistent (maya does not mean illusion in the sense of hallucination) but that its apparent separateness is misperceived. Seeing a rope as a snake in dim light is the classic example, the rope is real the misperception is the maya.',
'The distinction between maya as illusion (the world doesnt exist) and maya as mismeasurement (the world exists but its nature is misperceived) is crucial. Shankara never denies the practical reality of the world, he denies its ultimate reality as a collection of separate self-sufficient entities. The world is real as the expression of Brahman but unreal as a collection of separate things existing independently of Brahman.',
'Hindu philosophy maya illusion Brahman sacred ancient India',ARRAY['maya','hinduism','vedanta','illusion','brahman']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',12,50,
'Kashmir Shaivism''s concept of Pratyabhijna (recognition) teaches that liberation consists of:',
'["Recognising what was always already the case, that Shiva (universal consciousness) is the true nature of the individual self, a recognition not an achievement","Achieving through intensive practice a new state of consciousness that did not previously exist in the individual","Realising that the individual self is a temporary modification of the cosmic body and must be dissolved back into it","Understanding the philosophical arguments for non-dualism so completely that intellectual conviction transforms into lived reality"]',
0,'philosophical',
'The Pratyabhijna (Recognition) philosophy of Kashmir Shaivism developed by Utpaladeva and systematised by Abhinavagupta proposes that liberation is not achieved through a new state but through recognising what was always already present. The individual self has always been Shiva, infinite consciousness, but has forgotten this through the power of its own divine self-concealment. Liberation is the recognition of this already-existing identity.',
'The metaphor used by Kashmir Shaivism is striking: imagine a king who under the spell of amnesia wanders as a beggar. When someone shows him a mirror and he recognises himself the kingship is not newly achieved, it was always his. Similarly the individual soul recognising itself as Shiva is not becoming something new but remembering what it always was. This makes liberation not a distant future achievement but a present possibility, the next recognition.',
'Kashmir Shaivism recognition Shiva consciousness liberation India',ARRAY['kashmir shaivism','pratyabhijna','recognition','shiva','liberation']),

-- REALM 5: CONSCIOUSNESS (10 questions)
(5,'Consciousness',1,5,
'Near-death experiences (NDEs) are remarkable for cross-cultural consistency. Which element is most universally reported?',
'["A sensation of moving toward a brilliant overwhelmingly loving light","Meeting specific religious figures appropriate to the experiencers cultural background","A life review where all earthly experiences are re-experienced simultaneously","An out-of-body experience seeing ones physical body from above"]',
0,'empirical',
'Raymond Moody documented NDEs in Life After Life (1975) identifying consistent elements: leaving the body a dark tunnel a brilliant light of overwhelming love meeting deceased relatives or spiritual beings a panoramic life review and returning transformed with a profound loss of fear of death. The tunnel-and-light experience is reported across cultures ages and religious backgrounds with remarkable consistency.',
'The consistency of NDE phenomenology across cultures is precisely what makes it scientifically interesting and philosophically challenging. If NDEs were simply the brains dying hallucinations filtered through cultural expectations we would expect far greater cultural variation. The consistent core experience, the light described as infinitely loving and more real than ordinary reality, suggests something genuinely significant is occurring.',
'light consciousness near death experience bright tunnel',ARRAY['nde','near death','consciousness','afterlife','moody']),

(5,'Consciousness',1,5,
'The Default Mode Network (DMN) in neuroscience is active primarily during:',
'["Rest self-referential thought and mind-wandering, it is suppressed during focused tasks and strongly reduced by psychedelics and meditation","Processing sensory information from the external environment","Social cognition and understanding other peoples minds","Automatic functions like breathing and heartbeat, the brains autopilot system"]',
0,'empirical',
'The Default Mode Network is a set of brain regions active during resting states and deactivated during focused external tasks. It is associated with self-referential thought mind-wandering imagination of the future and the narrative construction of personal identity. Research shows psychedelics like psilocybin dramatically suppress DMN activity, correlating with ego dissolution and mystical states.',
'The DMN can be understood as the neural substrate of the ego, the brains mechanism for generating and maintaining the continuous narrative story of a separate self. When suppressed (through meditation psychedelics or certain disease states) people report experiences ranging from flow states to mystical union. This suggests that what we call the self is not an eternal soul but an active construction, precisely what Buddhist and Advaita traditions have taught for 2000 years.',
'brain MRI neural network consciousness neuroscience research',ARRAY['neuroscience','default mode network','ego','psychedelics']),

(5,'Consciousness',4,15,
'The hard problem of consciousness (David Chalmers 1995) refers to:',
'["Why and how subjective experience (qualia) arises from physical processes, why there is something it is like to be conscious","How the brain integrates information from multiple sensory systems into unified perception","Why consciousness evolved, what selective advantage does subjective awareness provide","How humans maintain continuous personal identity despite constant neural change"]',
0,'empirical',
'Chalmers distinguished between easy problems of consciousness (explaining how the brain processes information and reports internal states, mechanistic explanations) and the hard problem: why is there subjective experience at all? Why does neural activity produce qualia, the felt quality of redness the taste of coffee the ache of longing? This question has resisted all neuroscientific explanation.',
'The hard problem reveals a fundamental gap in the materialist worldview: all objective descriptions describe structure function and behaviour, never the intrinsic qualities of experience. This is not a problem that more brain imaging will solve, it is a conceptual gap. Some philosophers conclude consciousness must be fundamental to reality (panpsychism), perhaps what ancient traditions of the East were already pointing toward.',
'consciousness brain philosophy mind qualia experience science',ARRAY['hard problem','consciousness','qualia','philosophy of mind']),

(5,'Consciousness',4,15,
'Researcher Rick Strassman found that DMT (dimethyltryptamine) is endogenous, produced within the human body. Where has it been confirmed?',
'["In blood cerebrospinal fluid and the lungs, the pineal gland production hypothesis is popular but unconfirmed in humans","Exclusively in the pineal gland where it regulates the sleep-wake cycle","Only in the liver and adrenal glands during extreme psychological stress","In the retina only where it functions to filter visual information during dream states"]',
0,'empirical',
'Strassmans research (DMT: The Spirit Molecule) administered DMT to subjects and found consistent reports of encounters with intelligent entities geometric visions and experiences of alternate dimensions. Endogenous DMT has been confirmed in blood urine cerebrospinal fluid and the lungs. The popular pineal gland hypothesis has not been confirmed by direct measurement in living humans though it remains scientifically viable.',
'The endogenous presence of DMT, the same molecule responsible for some of the most profound altered states known, raises a fascinating question: might there be naturally occurring states (deep meditation hypnagogia near-death experiences) where its production is elevated? The fact that one of the most powerful psychedelic molecules is also a normal component of human biochemistry suggests the capacity for mystical experience may be hardwired into human biology.',
'DMT molecule brain research psychedelic pineal gland',ARRAY['dmt','endogenous','psychedelics','consciousness','strassman']),

(5,'Consciousness',12,50,
'Giulio Tononis Integrated Information Theory (IIT) proposes consciousness corresponds to phi. Its most controversial implication is:',
'["Any system with high integrated information has some degree of consciousness, including simple circuits, while some AI systems might have near-zero consciousness despite computational power","Consciousness is purely computational, sufficient processing power automatically generates subjective experience","The thalamus is the sole seat of consciousness, the cortex processes information without experiential quality","Consciousness is a quantum phenomenon exclusive to biological microtubules in neurons"]',
0,'empirical',
'IIT proposes that consciousness equals integrated information (phi), a measure of how much a systems whole generates more information than the sum of its parts. This implies any system with high phi has some degree of consciousness potentially including simple electronic circuits. It also implies that current AI feedforward networks might have near-zero consciousness while certain simple biological systems might have genuine experience.',
'IITs most radical implication is a form of structural panpsychism, consciousness is not exclusive to biological brains but is a property of certain organisational structures wherever they occur. This resonates with the Hermetic teaching that the All is Mind, that consciousness is a fundamental feature of reality rather than an exceptional biological property.',
'brain consciousness information neuroscience mind IIT theory',ARRAY['IIT','integrated information','Tononi','consciousness','panpsychism']),

(5,'Consciousness',12,50,
'Stanislav Grofs holotropic breathwork research suggested:',
'["Human consciousness contains transpersonal dimensions including what appear to be memories of biological birth ancestral experience and collective archetypes accessible through non-ordinary states","LSD produces hallucinations that are random neural noise with no psychological significance","The unconscious mind contains only personal repressed material with no collective dimension","Psychedelics are purely physiological, their psychological effects are entirely explained by serotonin receptor binding"]',
0,'empirical',
'Grof conducted over 4000 LSD sessions and observed experiences that transcended personal biography, including authentic re-experiences of birth trauma with physiological correlates apparent memories of ancestral events and what appeared to be experiences of cosmic consciousness death and rebirth and mythological content that matched cross-cultural traditions the subjects had no prior knowledge of.',
'Grofs research suggests human consciousness is vastly larger than ordinary waking awareness, containing within it a history extending beyond personal biography to biological birth evolutionary heritage and even cosmic dimensions. Whether these transpersonal experiences represent genuine access to realities beyond the individual psyche or very deep projections of universal cognitive structures they consistently produce the most therapeutically powerful experiences known to modern psychology.',
'holotropic breathwork consciousness therapy transpersonal psychology',ARRAY['grof','holotropic','LSD','transpersonal','consciousness']),

(5,'Consciousness',1,5,
'What distinguishes lucid dreaming from ordinary dreaming?',
'["The dreamer is aware they are dreaming while remaining in the dream state, allowing deliberate choice and navigation","The dream content is unusually vivid and emotionally intense, more real-seeming than ordinary dreams","The dreamer can receive accurate information about the external world while sleeping","The dream has symbolic meaning directly relating to the dreamers waking psychological situation"]',
0,'empirical',
'Lucid dreaming occurs when the dreamer becomes aware they are dreaming while remaining in the dream state. First scientifically confirmed by Keith Hearne (1975) and Stephen LaBerge (1980) using pre-agreed eye movement signals from within the dream state lucid dreaming has been extensively studied. Techniques include MILD (mnemonic induction) WILD (wake-induced) and reality testing.',
'Lucid dreaming provides a unique philosophical laboratory: a state in which consciousness is fully active and self-aware while the physical body is inert and sensory input is entirely internally generated. The lucid dreamers ability to observe the construction of an entire experiential world while knowing it is a mental construction offers a direct experiential demonstration of consciousness creative power.',
'lucid dreaming consciousness sleep REM dream state night',ARRAY['lucid dreaming','consciousness','sleep','laberge']),

(5,'Consciousness',4,15,
'The Tibetan Buddhist concept of rigpa refers to:',
'["The primordial awareness that underlies all mental states, the natural state of mind recognized in dzogchen practice as identical with the buddha nature","The practice of visualizing deities in meditative states to purify mental patterns through symbolic transformation","The recognition that all phenomena including the self are empty of inherent existence (sunyata)","The state of deep dreamless sleep in which consciousness becomes temporarily purified of all content"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Rigpa (Tibetan: knowledge awareness) is the central concept in Dzogchen, the highest teaching in the Nyingma school of Tibetan Buddhism. It refers to the primordial awareness or natural state of mind that underlies all ordinary mental activity: thoughts emotions perceptions. Rigpa is not achieved through practice, it is recognised as the ever-present foundation of experience. All of Dzogchen practice is aimed at recognising and stabilising in this natural state.',
'The dzogchen understanding of rigpa is structurally identical to the Kashmir Shaivism recognition (pratyabhijna) of Shiva and the Advaita recognition of Brahman: what is sought is not a new state but the recognition of what was always already present as the ground of all experience. The difference is cultural language not experiential content, suggesting these traditions are mapping the same territory from different starting points.',
'Tibetan Buddhism meditation consciousness Tibet mountains monastery',ARRAY['rigpa','dzogchen','tibetan buddhism','awareness','buddha nature']),

(5,'Consciousness',12,50,
'John Wheeler proposed that the universe is fundamentally participatory. What does this mean?',
'["Conscious observers are not passive spectators of a pre-existing reality but active participants whose observations help bring reality into being, no phenomenon is a phenomenon until observed","Consciousness creates matter through intention, focused thought can literally manifest physical objects in the external world","The universe is a simulation run by a higher-dimensional consciousness that responds to the collective beliefs of its participants","Human consciousness is the means by which the universe achieves self-awareness, we are the universes way of knowing itself"]',
0,'empirical',
'Wheeler coined the phrase "participatory universe" based on his delayed-choice experiment results: the decision to observe which path a photon took can apparently be made after the photon has already passed through the slits, yet the photon retroactively adjusts its behaviour. "No phenomenon is a phenomenon until it is an observed phenomenon." This implies that the past is not fully defined until information about it becomes irreversible.',
'Wheelers participatory universe is not idealism (mind creates matter) but something stranger: a universe in which the past is genuinely open until observation forecloses possibilities. The implication that reality is co-created connects quantum physics to participatory mystical traditions, the view that consciousness and universe are mutually arising rather than one being the passive background for the other.',
'quantum physics Wheeler participatory universe observation cosmos',ARRAY['wheeler','participatory universe','quantum physics','observation']),

-- REALM 6: PSYCHOLOGY (10 questions)
(6,'Psychology',1,5,
'Carl Jung proposed that beneath the personal unconscious lies:',
'["The collective unconscious, a layer shared by all humans containing universal archetypes and inherited psychological patterns","The superconscious, a higher dimension accessible only through deep meditation and spiritual practice","The racial unconscious, memories specific to ethnic groups preserved through epigenetics","The cosmic unconscious, a unified field connecting all minds through a quantum field"]',
0,'empirical',
'Jung proposed that beneath the personal unconscious lies the collective unconscious, a deeper layer shared by all humans containing archetypes: universal primordial patterns of psychic energy that structure human experience across all cultures, the hero shadow anima/animus wise old man great mother. Unlike the personal unconscious (acquired in one lifetime) the collective unconscious is inherited.',
'Jungs concept of the collective unconscious bridges psychology and anthropology explaining why the same themes appear in myths across cultures with no historical contact. Whether understood literally as a shared psychic field or metaphorically as a description of deep human commonalities the collective unconscious has proven enormously generative for psychotherapy mythology and understanding spiritual experience.',
'Jung psychology unconscious archetypes mandala circle',ARRAY['jung','collective unconscious','archetypes','psychology']),

(6,'Psychology',1,5,
'In Jungian psychology the Shadow refers to:',
'["The collection of repressed denied and rejected aspects of the personality that operate unconsciously","The mask or persona we show to the world to meet social expectations","The unconscious contrasexual element in men (anima) and women (animus)","The autonomous complexes formed around traumatic childhood experiences"]',
0,'empirical',
'The Shadow contains everything the conscious ego refuses to identify with, qualities considered unacceptable weak or immoral as well as genuine positive qualities rejected by the childhood environment (the golden shadow). The Shadow is the repository of unlived life. When not integrated it is projected outward onto others, scapegoating prejudice and tribal hatred are collective Shadow projections.',
'The Shadows most important characteristic is that it does not disappear when ignored, it grows in power. Every quality we refuse to acknowledge in ourselves gets projected onto others and becomes visible as an intense reaction toward those qualities in other people. The person you most intensely dislike often carries qualities belonging to your own Shadow, an insight that makes shadow work both personally liberating and essential for social understanding.',
'shadow psychology darkness integration unconscious Jung',ARRAY['jung','shadow','psychology','shadow work','projection']),

(6,'Psychology',4,15,
'Jung defined individuation as:',
'["The lifelong process of integrating all parts of the psyche into a conscious differentiated whole centred on the Self rather than the ego","The developmental stages through which a child becomes a socialised member of their cultural group","The process by which repressed trauma memories are recovered and integrated into conscious awareness","The differentiation of psychological types (introvert/extrovert) that determines personality"]',
0,'empirical',
'Individuation is the emergence of the individual Self from original undifferentiated wholeness. It involves integrating the persona (social mask) confronting and integrating the Shadow engaging with the anima/animus (contrasexual inner figures) and ultimately centring identity on the Self (the totality of the psyche both conscious and unconscious) rather than the ego alone. Individuation is a lifelong journey, never complete.',
'Individuation is essentially what all genuine spiritual traditions describe as awakening translated into psychological language. The difference is that Jungian individuation does not require transcendence of the ego or union with a metaphysical absolute, it requires a reorientation of the egos relationship to the whole psyche. The goal is not to become egoless but to become ego-conscious: aware that the ego is a part of a larger wholeness.',
'individuation psychology Jung mandala wholeness growth integration',ARRAY['jung','individuation','self','psychology','wholeness']),

(6,'Psychology',4,15,
'Jung coined synchronicity to describe:',
'["Meaningful coincidences, acausal connections between inner psychic events and outer physical events that share meaning but not physical causation","A phenomenon where charged emotional states cause people to fall into identical thinking patterns simultaneously","The unconscious tendency of therapy patients to pattern their behaviour on the therapists expectations","Dreams that accurately predict future external events"]',
0,'empirical',
'Jung defined synchronicity as an acausal connecting principle, meaningful coincidence between an inner (psychic) event and an outer (physical) event sharing meaning but connected by no physical cause-and-effect. The classic example: a patient describes a dream about a golden scarab beetle when an actual scarab-like insect taps on Jungs window. Jung saw synchronicity as evidence that psyche and matter participate in a common underlying order.',
'Synchronicity remains one of the most philosophically rich and empirically problematic of Jungs contributions. Physicists Wolfgang Pauli and David Bohm engaged with the concept seriously wondering if it points to a deeper order beneath the apparent separation of mind and matter. If mind and matter share a common underlying order then meaningful coincidences are windows into a more fundamental connectedness.',
'synchronicity coincidence meaningful universe signs patterns',ARRAY['jung','synchronicity','meaningful coincidence','pauli']),

(6,'Psychology',12,50,
'Joseph Campbell identified what three main stages of the heroes journey?',
'["Departure from the ordinary world, Initiation through trials and transformation, Return bringing wisdom back to the community","Childhood innocence, Crisis the wound or loss, Transcendence the achieved spirituality","Ego ordinary consciousness, Shadow encounter with darkness, Self achievement of wholeness through integration","Innocence, Experience, Higher Innocence, the three stages of William Blakes spiritual evolution"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Campbell identified the monomyth structure in The Hero with a Thousand Faces (1949). The hero receives a call to adventure crosses a threshold into an extraordinary world faces tests and allies reaches the innermost cave where the central ordeal occurs seizes the reward and makes the road back, transformed and ready to bring wisdom to the ordinary world.',
'The monomyth is not just a literary pattern, it is a map of psychological transformation. Every stage corresponds to a psychological challenge: the call is the emergence of the unconscious into consciousness; the initiation is the confrontation with the Shadow and death of the old self; the return is the integration of what has been learned. The same story, whether Star Wars the Odyssey or a shamanic initiation, produces the same recognition across all cultures.',
'hero journey myth adventure quest transformation voyage',ARRAY['campbell','monomyth','hero journey','mythology','archetypes']),

(6,'Psychology',12,50,
'Viktor Frankls logotherapy proposes that the primary human motivation is:',
'["The search for meaning, and meaning can be found even in unavoidable suffering through the attitude one takes toward it","The will to pleasure, and suffering is always a sign of blocked or frustrated pleasure-seeking","The will to power, and suffering results from not having sufficient mastery over ones environment","The avoidance of death anxiety, and all human activity is ultimately motivated by terror management"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Frankl developed logotherapy based on his observation in Nazi concentration camps that those most likely to survive were not the physically strongest but those who had a reason to live, a purpose someone to return to a work to complete. He proposed that the primary human motivation is the will to meaning (contra Freuds will to pleasure and Adlers will to power) and that meaning can be found even in unavoidable suffering.',
'Frankls insight, that we cannot always choose our circumstances but can always choose our response to them, converges with both Stoic philosophy and Buddhist teachings on acceptance of dukkha. He who has a why to live can bear almost any how. The idea that meaning provides the psychological resources to endure anything has proven one of the most clinically effective ideas in all of psychotherapy.',
'Viktor Frankl meaning suffering philosophy psychology concentration camp',ARRAY['frankl','logotherapy','meaning','will to meaning','suffering']),

(6,'Psychology',1,5,
'The Jungian concept of persona refers to:',
'["The social mask or public face we present to the world, necessary for social functioning but dangerous when identified with","The authentic self that emerges through the individuation process","The shadow side of the personality that contains repressed qualities","The inner image of the ideal partner projected onto actual romantic partners"]',
0,'empirical',
'The persona (Latin: mask) is the social face presented to the world, the professional identity the cultural role the image crafted to meet social expectations. The persona is not inherently false, we need different faces for different contexts. The danger Jung called persona identification occurs when a person mistakes the mask for themselves, when the doctor forgets they are not only a doctor.',
'The persona system is one of Jungs most immediately recognisable concepts because we can all observe it directly in ourselves. The spiritual danger of persona identification is the same as what the Gnostics called hylics who cannot perceive the divine spark within them: so thoroughly do they identify with the social role that the deeper selfhood which the persona exists to protect is forgotten entirely.',
'mask persona psychology role social identity performance',ARRAY['jung','persona','mask','psychology','social identity']),

(6,'Psychology',4,15,
'Jungs concept of the anima and animus refers to:',
'["The unconscious contrasexual element in the psyche, the feminine image in men (anima) and masculine image in women (animus), which mediates between ego and the deeper unconscious","The ideal romantic partner as constructed by the personal unconscious based on early caregiving experiences","The spiritual guide or inner teacher that appears in dreams as a figure of wisdom and authority","The protective function of the psyche that creates a barrier between consciousness and overwhelming unconscious content"]',
0,'empirical',
'The anima (in men) and animus (in women) are what Jung called soul figures, autonomous complexes that carry the contrasexual aspects of the psyche and mediate between ego consciousness and the deeper layers of the unconscious. The anima tends to appear in mens dreams as female figures ranging from the seductive temptress to the wise spiritual guide. The animus appears in womens dreams as male figures ranging from the brute to the wise sage.',
'The anima/animus dynamic explains much of what drives intense romantic projections: when we fall deeply in love we are often projecting our inner soul figure onto the beloved. The beloved appears to embody qualities we have not yet integrated in ourselves, which is why romantic love is simultaneously so revelatory and so inevitably disillusioning as the projection is withdrawn and the actual person is encountered.',
'Jung psychology anima animus feminine masculine archetype',ARRAY['jung','anima','animus','psychology','archetypes']),

(6,'Psychology',12,50,
'Jungs collective unconscious and Ruperts Sheldrakes morphic field theory share what conceptual parallel?',
'["Both propose an invisible non-local field that stores and transmits patterns across individuals of the same species, psychological archetypes vs morphic resonance","Both claim that physical laws are actually habits that evolved over time rather than eternal mathematical truths","Both propose that human consciousness after death joins a collective field that can be accessed by future generations through meditation","Both are rejected by mainstream science as pseudoscience while being embraced by the New Age movement for the same reasons"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Jungs collective unconscious proposes that psychological patterns (archetypes) are inherited by individuals not through personal memory but through a field shared by the species. Sheldrakes morphic field theory proposes that biological organisms inherit behavioural and structural patterns not only through DNA but through a non-local morphic field that accumulates the habits of the species. Both propose information transmission that bypasses conventional physical mechanisms.',
'The Sheldrake-Jung parallel is one of the most thought-provoking in science and psychology. Both thinkers identified phenomena that conventional biology and psychology could not explain (why do rat populations learn mazes faster after other rats have learned them even with no physical contact? why do humans worldwide dream the same archetypes without cultural transmission?) and proposed similar non-local field solutions. Whether these fields are real or metaphorical remains deeply contested.',
'morphic field consciousness species inheritance Jung Sheldrake',ARRAY['jung','sheldrake','morphic field','collective unconscious','non-local']),

-- REALM 7: QUANTUM PHYSICS (10 questions)
(7,'Quantum Physics',1,5,
'The double-slit experiment demonstrates that electrons and photons:',
'["Behave as waves producing interference patterns when not observed but as particles when measured, the act of measurement collapses the wave function","Always behave as particles, wave behaviour is a statistical artifact of large numbers of particles","Produce interference patterns only when fired at high velocity; slow particles behave as pure particles","Switch between wave and particle depending on temperature, cold particles behave as waves"]',
0,'empirical',
'Individual electrons fired one at a time at a barrier with two slits create an interference pattern on the detector screen, as if each electron passes through both slits simultaneously and interferes with itself. However when a detector is placed to observe which slit the electron passes through the interference pattern disappears and electrons behave as particles. This is the measurement problem, one of the most profound and unresolved puzzles in physics.',
'The double-slit experiment puts in stark experimental form the deepest mystery of quantum mechanics: the role of observation in determining physical reality. Before measurement the electron exists in a superposition of all possible states, simultaneously going through both slits. The act of measurement collapses this superposition into a definite state. Whether this collapse is physical informational or involves consciousness remains deeply contested.',
'quantum physics laboratory double slit wave particle experiment',ARRAY['quantum physics','double slit','wave particle duality','measurement']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',1,5,
'Quantum entanglement describes:',
'["When two particles are correlated such that measuring one instantly affects the others state regardless of the distance between them","When particles become physically linked and must be physically separated to end their connection","A quantum force field exchanged between particles at the speed of light when separated","The tendency of identical particles to cluster together creating molecular bonds"]',
0,'empirical',
'When two particles become entangled they share a quantum state. Measuring one particle and collapsing its quantum state instantly correlates with the other particles state regardless of distance. Bells theorem (confirmed by Alain Aspect in 1982) demonstrated that no local hidden variable theory can explain these correlations, the universe is genuinely non-local at the quantum level.',
'Quantum entanglements non-locality suggests that at the most fundamental level the universe does not consist of separate objects that interact through forces. Entangled particles remain a single system regardless of spatial separation. David Bohms interpretation suggests this points to an underlying implicate order in which everything is enfolded into everything else, a holographic universe where separation is a feature of the surface order rather than a fundamental fact.',
'quantum entanglement particles physics laboratory non-local',ARRAY['quantum entanglement','non-locality','Bell theorem','quantum physics']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',4,15,
'David Bohms implicate order proposes that:',
'["The visible physical world (explicate order) is a projection from a deeper enfolded dimension (implicate order) where all things are holographically interconnected","Quantum mechanics is incomplete and hidden variables determine the apparent randomness of quantum events","The universe operates like a neural network where particles communicate through quantum fields","Reality consists of parallel orders, the physical and mental, that operate independently but occasionally interact"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Physicist David Bohm proposed that the universe has two levels: the explicate order (the visible world of separate objects and events) and the implicate order (a deeper dimension where everything is enfolded into everything else like patterns in a hologram). The explicate order is a continuous projection from the implicate. Entanglement and non-locality are explainable because apparently separated particles are still connected at the implicate level.',
'Bohms implicate order is one of the few scientific frameworks that directly parallels ancient mystical cosmologies: an underlying Unity from which apparent multiplicity emerges and to which it remains connected. It resonates with Indras net in Buddhism Hermetic correspondence and the Gnostic Pleroma. Bohm collaborated with Krishnamurti for decades exploring where physics and consciousness research overlap.',
'holographic universe physics implicate order cosmos Bohm',ARRAY['bohm','implicate order','holographic universe','quantum physics']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',4,15,
'The holographic principle in theoretical physics proposes that:',
'["All information describing a volume of space is encoded on its two-dimensional boundary, the universe may be fundamentally a hologram","Reality is composed of light frequencies that our brains decode into a three-dimensional experience","Consciousness creates holographic reality through the observer effect in quantum mechanics","The universe repeats itself at every scale, galaxies mirror atoms in structure"]',
0,'empirical',
'The holographic principle arising from black hole physics proposes that the maximum information encodable in a region of space is proportional to its surface area not its volume. This suggests our apparently 3-dimensional universe could be the holographic projection of information encoded on a 2-dimensional boundary. The principle is a theorem in string theory (AdS/CFT correspondence).',
'Michael Talbots The Holographic Universe (1991) popularised the idea that the holographic principle might explain both quantum physics and anomalous consciousness phenomena. Neuroscientist Karl Pribram had already proposed the brain works holographically. If both brain and universe operate on holographic principles consciousness and physical reality may share a deeper structural kinship, the as above so below of Hermetic thought may have a scientific substrate.',
'holographic universe space information physics theory cosmos',ARRAY['holographic principle','information physics','universe','quantum gravity']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',12,50,
'John Wheelers delayed choice experiment suggests that:',
'["An observers decision whether to measure which path a photon took can apparently affect the photons behaviour retroactively, the past is not fixed until observed","The future determines the present through backward causation","Consciousness can choose which quantum branch of reality to experience making free will scientifically viable","Observation affects quantum systems only at the moment of observation not before or after"]',
0,'empirical',
'Wheelers delayed-choice experiment (confirmed 2007) demonstrates that the decision to observe which slit a photon passes through can be made after the photon has already passed through the slits, yet the photon retroactively adjusts its behaviour to match the observation. If the measurement is made no interference pattern forms; if not the interference pattern is present.',
'Wheeler concluded the universe is participatory, observers are not passive spectators but active participants in bringing reality into being. No phenomenon is a phenomenon until it is an observed phenomenon. The implication that reality is fundamentally open and co-created connects quantum physics to participatory mystical traditions, the view that consciousness and universe are co-arising.',
'quantum physics experiment laboratory photon light measurement',ARRAY['wheeler','delayed choice','quantum physics','observer','participatory']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',12,50,
'What is the measurement problem in quantum mechanics?',
'["Quantum systems exist in superposition (multiple states simultaneously) until measured, but physics cannot explain what constitutes a measurement or why measurement collapses the superposition","Quantum measurements always introduce uncertainty due to the observer disturbing the system","The equations of quantum mechanics cannot make precise predictions, only probabilistic ones","Quantum systems cannot be measured at absolute zero temperature because measurement itself introduces thermal energy"]',
0,'empirical',
'The measurement problem: quantum mechanics mathematically describes particles existing in superpositions of multiple states simultaneously. When measured the wave function collapses to a single definite state. But the theory provides no physical mechanism for this collapse, why does observation produce a definite outcome? Proposed solutions include Copenhagen (collapse is real but unexplained) Many Worlds (all outcomes occur in branching parallel universes) and QBism (quantum states are subjective beliefs).',
'The measurement problem is not merely a technical puzzle, it is a profound philosophical crisis for the materialist worldview. Materialism assumes a physical world existing independently of observation. Quantum mechanics suggests at minimum that the mathematical description of physical systems depends fundamentally on observation. Whether this implicates consciousness in the constitution of reality remains the deepest open question in the philosophy of physics.',
'quantum measurement superposition physics wave function collapse',ARRAY['measurement problem','superposition','wave function','quantum physics']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',4,15,
'Max Planck who founded quantum theory made what profound statement about the nature of matter and consciousness?',
'["He concluded that consciousness is fundamental and matter is derivative of it, science can never penetrate behind consciousness because everything we call real is made of things that cannot be regarded as real","He concluded that quantum physics proves the mind can directly manipulate physical reality through focused intention","He concluded that matter and consciousness are parallel manifestations of a single underlying mathematical structure","He concluded that the equations of quantum mechanics describe consciousness directly since they are fundamentally about information not physical objects"]',
0,'empirical',
'Max Planck stated: "I regard consciousness as fundamental. I regard matter as derivative from consciousness. We cannot get behind consciousness. Everything that we talk about everything that we regard as existing postulates consciousness." This statement from the founder of quantum theory, who was also deeply religious and philosophical, represents a remarkable convergence between the scientific pioneer who discovered the quantum and the idealist philosophical tradition.',
'That the founder of quantum theory concluded that consciousness is more fundamental than matter is one of the most striking and underreported facts in the history of science. Planck arrived at this conclusion not despite his scientific work but because of it, the deeper he penetrated into the mathematical structure of reality the less it resembled the materialist universe of the 19th century and the more it resembled the consciousness-first metaphysics of the great idealist philosophers.',
'Max Planck quantum physics consciousness matter universe science',ARRAY['planck','quantum physics','consciousness','matter','idealism']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',4,15,
'Schrodingers cat thought experiment was designed to illustrate:',
'["The absurdity of applying quantum superposition to macroscopic objects, if quantum mechanics is complete a cat must be simultaneously alive and dead until observed which seems absurd","The ethical problems with scientific experimentation on animals","The relationship between observer consciousness and quantum collapse, the cats consciousness collapses the wave function","That quantum mechanics applies only to subatomic particles and breaks down at larger scales"]',
0,'empirical',
'Erwin Schrodinger designed the thought experiment (1935) as a reductio ad absurdum to critique the Copenhagen interpretation. If quantum superposition applies to macroscopic objects then a cat inside a sealed box (where its fate is linked to a quantum event) must be simultaneously alive and dead until observed. Schrodinger intended to show that quantum superposition cannot be taken literally at the macroscopic scale, something must resolve the superposition before observation.',
'The cat paradox has haunted quantum physics for 90 years because it is genuinely unresolved. In the Copenhagen interpretation the wave function is not physically real, it is a mathematical tool for calculating probabilities. In the Many Worlds interpretation both outcomes actually occur in branching parallel universes. In decoherence theories the interaction with the environment collapses the superposition before any conscious observation. Each solution has profound implications for the nature of reality consciousness and the self.',
'Schrodinger cat quantum physics paradox superposition thought experiment',ARRAY['schrodinger','cat paradox','superposition','quantum physics','measurement']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',12,50,
'What is quantum decoherence and how does it attempt to solve the measurement problem?',
'["When a quantum system interacts with its environment the superposition effectively collapses through information spreading into the environment, without requiring a conscious observer, making quantum behaviour invisible at macroscopic scales","When quantum particles interact they transfer their quantum properties to each other decohering into classical particles with definite states","The process by which quantum fields decay into elementary particles after the Big Bang, quantum decoherence describes how the early universe lost its quantum nature","The tendency of quantum computers to lose their quantum information through environmental interference making them difficult to build"]',
0,'empirical',
'Quantum decoherence proposes that when a quantum system interacts with its environment the quantum information spreads into the environment irreversibly effectively collapsing the superposition, not through a conscious observer but through the thermodynamic irreversibility of the interaction with billions of environmental particles. This explains why macroscopic objects appear classical without requiring consciousness to play a special role.',
'Decoherence is widely accepted as explaining why we dont see quantum superposition in everyday life. But it does not fully solve the measurement problem: it explains why we observe definite outcomes but not which specific outcome we observe from a probability distribution. The remaining question, why this outcome rather than that one, still has no physical answer. Consciousness may still play a role that decoherence does not eliminate.',
'quantum decoherence physics environment interaction measurement',ARRAY['decoherence','quantum physics','measurement problem','environment']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',1,5,
'Werner Heisenbergs uncertainty principle states that:',
'["The more precisely the position of a particle is known the less precisely its momentum can be known, not due to measurement error but due to a fundamental feature of nature","Uncertainty about quantum particles is purely due to the limitations of our measurement technology","The act of measuring a particle necessarily disturbs it changing its actual state","All knowledge in physics is probabilistic, true certainty about any physical quantity is impossible even in principle"]',
0,'empirical',
'Heisenbergs uncertainty principle (1927) states that the product of the uncertainties in position and momentum of a particle can never be less than a specific constant (h/4pi). This is not a limitation of measurement technology, it is a fundamental feature of quantum reality. A particle does not simultaneously have a perfectly defined position and momentum. The more precisely one is defined the more fundamentally uncertain the other becomes.',
'The uncertainty principle is often misunderstood as saying we cannot know both position and momentum because measurement disturbs them. The deeper truth is that a quantum particle before measurement does not have definite values for both simultaneously, the definiteness of one property is fundamentally incompatible with the definiteness of the other. Reality at the quantum level is irreducibly probabilistic in a way that has no analogue in classical physics.',
'Heisenberg uncertainty principle quantum physics wave function',ARRAY['heisenberg','uncertainty principle','quantum physics','probability']),

-- REALM 8: ESOTERIC SCIENCE (10 questions)
(8,'Esoteric Science',1,5,
'The Ra Material (Law of One) identifies what as the fundamental nature of the universe?',
'["Intelligent infinity, one infinite consciousness that seeks to know itself through all of creation","A binary system of Light and Dark forces in eternal conflict for the souls of third-density beings","A quantum field from which all matter emerges anticipating modern quantum field theory","A multiverse of infinite parallel realities each containing different versions of all beings"]',
0,'channeled',
'The Ra Material presents Ra as a sixth-density collective consciousness communicating the Law of One: the singular principle that all things are one, that the apparent diversity of creation is the One Infinite Creator exploring itself through infinite configurations of consciousness. Ra describes reality as composed of distortions of Intelligent Infinity, free will being the first distortion love the second light the third.',
'The Law of One framework demonstrates remarkable internal consistency across hundreds of sessions. It presents a cosmology where consciousness is the only reality where free will is the most sacred principle and where all evolutionary trajectories, however long or difficult, ultimately return to the One. The framework resonates with Advaita Vedanta certain Gnostic cosmologies and aspects of modern consciousness research.',
'Ra Material Law One cosmic consciousness energy universe channeling',ARRAY['law of one','ra material','channeling','consciousness']),

(8,'Esoteric Science',1,5,
'Bashar channeled by Darryl Anka teaches that the most reliable guide to ones highest life path is:',
'["Acting on the highest excitement available in each moment, excitement being the compass of the higher self","Following the astrological configuration of ones birth chart as the blueprint for life purpose","Meditating daily to receive direct transmissions from ones higher self through dreams and synchronicity","Studying the Law of One to understand which density level one is currently evolving through"]',
0,'channeled',
'Bashars core teaching centres on excitement as the compass, the idea that the highest vibrational state available to you in any given moment is the direction your higher self is guiding you. This is not excitement as hedonism but as resonance, the state that aligns your present frequency with the highest version of your probable reality.',
'Whatever the metaphysical status of channeled material Bashars core teachings stand as elegant personal philosophy: belief precedes experience (not the reverse); reality consists of infinite parallel realities between which we shift based on our state of being; and fear is excitement without permission. These principles applied consistently demonstrably shift the quality of experience, which may be the only relevant empirical test for personal transformation teachings.',
'Bashar channeling cosmic consciousness stars universe Essassani',ARRAY['bashar','essassani','channeling','parallel reality','excitement']),

(8,'Esoteric Science',4,15,
'In the Law of One what characterises the third density in which humans currently exist?',
'["The veil of forgetting, the inability to consciously remember other incarnations, which enables genuine free will choices between service-to-others and service-to-self","Humanitys position in the third of nine physical dimensions, the densest form of matter in the local universe","The third historical era of Earths development, beginning with the emergence of agriculture and civilisation","Three-dimensional physicality as opposed to the higher-dimensional realities of advanced beings"]',
0,'channeled',
'The Law of One presents densities as qualitative levels of consciousness evolution. Third density is characterised by the veil of forgetting, the inability to consciously remember other incarnations or the nature of the greater self, which makes genuine moral choice possible. Without the veil beings would automatically choose love/service because they would see clearly. The veil ensures choices are made based on inner guidance rather than certainty.',
'The veil of forgetting is one of the Law of Ones most philosophically sophisticated concepts: genuine growth in consciousness requires genuine risk. If all beings automatically saw the loving unity of all things there would be no real choice no real testing and therefore no real development. The struggle and confusion of third-density existence is not a mistake or divine cruelty, it is the precisely calibrated condition that makes authentic evolution possible.',
'consciousness evolution densities spiritual growth universe cosmic Law One',ARRAY['law of one','densities','third density','veil','service']),

(8,'Esoteric Science',4,15,
'Dolores Cannons QHHT (Quantum Healing Hypnosis Technique) sessions consistently reported the Higher Self claiming to be:',
'["A vast wise part of the soul that retains all memories of all incarnations and can access information about the clients life health and purpose","The universal Akashic Records, a cosmic library accessible to all humans during deep trance","A collective of ascended masters who guide humanity through individual channels","The quantum field itself, a fundamental aspect of physical reality that encodes consciousness"]',
0,'channeled',
'Cannon spent 45+ years in regressive hypnosis. The intelligence she called the Higher Self emerged in deep trance states claiming to be an aspect of the clients soul that exists beyond the current incarnation has lived many lives retains perfect memory of all of them and can access information the conscious mind does not have. This entity consistently demonstrated the ability to diagnose and sometimes heal physical conditions.',
'Cannons body of work, including the Convoluted Universe series and thousands of documented QHHT sessions, presents a consistent picture convergently mapping onto the Law of One Seth Material and other channeled cosmologies: each human is a fragment of an infinite consciousness that incarnates repeatedly for learning and evolution. Whether this represents genuine contact with a higher aspect of consciousness or sophisticated deep-mind confabulation the cross-cultural consistency across thousands of subjects is remarkable.',
'hypnosis spiritual regression past lives consciousness healing QHHT',ARRAY['dolores cannon','QHHT','past lives','higher self','regression']),

(8,'Esoteric Science',12,50,
'Helena Blavatskys Theosophy proposed that all world religions and philosophies share:',
'["A common ancient wisdom tradition transmitted through successive root races and preserved by a Brotherhood of Masters (Mahatmas)","A common psychological origin in humanitys fear of death, theology as elaborate denial of mortality","A common empirical core accessible through comparative religion stripped of cultural accretions","A common evolutionary impulse, each tradition representing a stage in humanitys linear development toward monotheism"]',
0,'esoteric',
'Blavatskys Theosophy (The Secret Doctrine 1888) proposed that all world religions derive from a single ancient wisdom tradition, the Wisdom Religion, transmitted across civilisations by a Brotherhood of Masters (Mahatmas) who preserve and selectively reveal esoteric knowledge. She introduced concepts of seven root races cosmic cycles and the evolution of consciousness through successive rounds.',
'Theosophy was arguably the most influential esoteric movement of the 19th century, directly generating the New Age movement influencing Rudolf Steiners Anthroposophy inspiring Krishnamurti and shaping the spiritual landscape of the 20th century. Blavatskys synthesis, however controversial in its details, established the modern framework of universal spiritual evolution that underlies much contemporary spirituality.',
'Theosophy Blavatsky ancient wisdom Mahatma mystical esoteric',ARRAY['theosophy','blavatsky','perennial philosophy','mahatmas']),

(8,'Esoteric Science',12,50,
'The Seth Material channeled by Jane Roberts most notably challenges mainstream reality with the teaching:',
'["You create your own reality through the power of belief, beliefs not external events are the primary determinants of experienced reality","Seth was an extraterrestrial being from Sirius who transmitted his civilisations complete scientific and philosophical knowledge","The universe is a dream of God that will end when God awakens, all individual consciousness will cease to exist","Physical reality is a shared illusion maintained by a cosmic agreement among all souls before incarnation"]',
0,'channeled',
'The Seth Material centres on you create your own reality, the idea that conscious and unconscious beliefs are the primary creative mechanisms determining the nature of experienced reality. Seth taught that the universe is not a mechanistic system happening to consciousness but a creative field shaped by the beliefs emotions and expectations of the consciousnesses within it.',
'The Seth Materials influence on modern spirituality is vast, the contemporary law of attraction paradigm traces directly to Seths teachings. Whether understood literally (beliefs literally create material reality) or psychologically (beliefs shape perception and behaviour which shape outcomes) the core insight has proven transformative for millions. Seths teaching sits at the intersection of quantum physics Jungian psychology and mystical traditions of all cultures.',
'Seth Material Jane Roberts channeling consciousness reality books',ARRAY['seth material','jane roberts','channeling','create reality','beliefs']),

(8,'Esoteric Science',1,5,
'Michael Newtons Between Lives research (Journey of Souls 1994) describes what consistent between-lives experience?',
'["Return to a spirit world where souls review their life meet their soul group and plan the next incarnation with guides","An immediate reincarnation into the next available body with no gap between physical lives","A gradual dissolution of individual consciousness into a universal cosmic field until a new identity crystallises","A period in a realm matched to the souls current vibrational level ranging from darkness to pure light"]',
0,'channeled',
'Newton conducted over 7000 deep hypnosis sessions in which subjects consistently reported similar between-lives experiences: review of the completed life meeting with a guide or council of elders reuniting with their soul group (a cluster of souls who incarnate repeatedly together) selecting lessons and planning the next life and often choosing their future body and circumstances.',
'Newtons research along with Cannons and Weisss parallel work presents a surprisingly consistent picture of the between-lives state mapping closely onto descriptions in the Tibetan Book of the Dead Platos Myth of Er and the Law of Ones description of the harvesting and planning process between incarnations. Whether this convergence reflects genuine contact with a consistent post-mortem reality or a shared deep cognitive architecture remains genuinely open.',
'between lives soul spirit world Michael Newton regression hypnosis',ARRAY['michael newton','between lives','soul groups','reincarnation']),

(8,'Esoteric Science',4,15,
'The Council of Nine as channeled through Phyllis Schlemmer and others claims to be:',
'["Nine cosmic intelligences who have guided humanity since ancient times associated with the ancient Egyptian Ennead (nine primordial gods)","The nine members of an intergalactic governing council maintaining peace between star civilisations","The nine primary rays of creation from which all consciousness in this universe emerges","The collective consciousness of nine ancient civilisations that achieved transcendence and merged into a single cosmic mind"]',
0,'channeled',
'The Council of Nine material, channeled across multiple decades starting with the 1952 Puharich sessions through to Phyllis Schlemmers The Only Planet of Choice, claims to be nine cosmic intelligences associated with the ancient Egyptian Ennead (the nine primordial deities of the Heliopolis creation myth). The Nine describe themselves as administrators of our galaxy concerned with Earths evolution during a crucial transitional period.',
'The Council of Nine material occupies fascinating cultural territory: its sessions in the 1950s involved prominent scientists and intellectuals and the material influenced early New Age thought significantly. The connection to the Egyptian Ennead suggests either a genuine continuity of transmitted wisdom from ancient Egypt or a sophisticated modern mythological construction. The book The Only Planet of Choice remains one of the most unusual and internally consistent channeled documents of the 20th century.',
'Council Nine cosmic intelligence Egypt Ennead ancient gods universe',ARRAY['council of nine','channeling','ennead','ancient egypt']),

(8,'Esoteric Science',12,50,
'Rudolph Steiners Anthroposophy differs from Blavatskys Theosophy primarily in that:',
'["Steiner centred spiritual science on the Christ event as the pivotal turning point in cosmic evolution and emphasised the development of new cognitive faculties to perceive spiritual realities","Steiner rejected all Eastern spiritual traditions as inappropriate for Western consciousness unlike Blavatsky who synthesised East and West","Steiner claimed direct clairvoyant perception of the Akashic Records without any need for masters or transmitted teaching","Steiner denied the reality of karma and reincarnation unlike Blavatsky who placed them at the centre of Theosophy"]',
0,'esoteric',
'Rudolf Steiner (1861-1925) was initially a member of the Theosophical Society but broke to found Anthroposophy (wisdom of the human being). While accepting reincarnation karma and spiritual evolution he placed the Christ event (the incarnation death and resurrection of Jesus) at the absolute centre of cosmic evolution, as the pivotal turning point when the cosmic Sun Being incarnated into Earth evolution. He also emphasised developing new cognitive faculties (imagination inspiration intuition) to perceive spiritual reality directly.',
'Steiners contributions span an extraordinary range: the Waldorf education system biodynamic agriculture anthroposophical medicine eurythmy (movement art) and extensive writings on karma and reincarnation, all derived from his claimed direct clairvoyant research of the Akashic Records. Whatever one thinks of the metaphysical claims the practical applications (Waldorf schools biodynamic farms) have proven remarkably durable and beneficial demonstrating that esoteric philosophy can generate effective real-world applications.',
'Rudolf Steiner Anthroposophy spiritual science biodynamic Waldorf',ARRAY['steiner','anthroposophy','theosophy','spiritual science','christ']),

(8,'Esoteric Science',4,15,
'The concept of the Akashic Records found across multiple esoteric traditions refers to:',
'["A cosmic memory or field that contains the complete record of every thought word and deed throughout the history of the universe, accessible through deep meditation or hypnotic regression","A physical repository of ancient wisdom texts hidden in secret underground libraries in Tibet and Egypt accessible only to initiates","The collective memory of the human species stored in the quantum vacuum field and accessible through certain altered states of consciousness","A Theosophical term for the Jungian collective unconscious, both referring to the same psychological phenomenon from different vocabularies"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Akashic Records (from Sanskrit akasha, ether sky) appear in Theosophy (Blavatsky Steiner) in Edgar Cayces readings in many channeled traditions and in various shamanic and mystical systems. The concept holds that all experiences and knowledge are permanently impressed upon a subtle field of reality that underlies ordinary spacetime and can be accessed through specific altered states of consciousness deep meditation or regression hypnosis.',
'The Akashic Records concept is remarkably consistent across traditions that had no historical contact with each other, from the shamanic world-tree that stores all knowledge to the Buddhist Alaya-vijnana (storehouse consciousness) to the Jungian collective unconscious. Whether understood literally (as an actual cosmic information field) or metaphorically (as a description of the depths of collective human memory) the concept points at something that human experience consistently encounters when consciousness goes deep enough.',
'Akashic Records cosmic memory field consciousness ancient wisdom',ARRAY['akashic records','cosmic memory','theosophy','consciousness','edgar cayce']),

-- REALM 9: COMPARATIVE RELIGION (10 questions)
(9,'Comparative Religion',1,5,
'In Sufism fana refers to:',
'["The annihilation or dissolution of the ego-self in union with God, the mystical death of the personal self","The 40-day solitary retreat practiced by advanced Sufi seekers","The sacred poetry tradition using music and dance to access divine union","The Sufi concept of the heart as the true spiritual centre of the human being"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Fana (Arabic: annihilation passing away) is the Sufi term for the mystical state in which the individual ego dissolves in union with the Divine. The personal self, with its desires attachments and sense of separate existence, ceases to function as the centre of experience. What remains is baqa (subsistence in God), the individual continues to function in the world but from the perspective of unity rather than separation.',
'Al-Hallaj was executed in 922 CE for declaring I am the Truth, interpreted as blasphemy (claiming to be God) rather than as a mystical statement about the dissolution of self in divine unity. The theological controversy around fana reveals a fundamental tension in theistic mysticism: how does the mystics experience of unity with God relate to orthodox doctrine of Gods absolute transcendence? Sufisms answer: both are true simultaneously.',
'Sufi whirling dervish mysticism Islamic meditation prayer',ARRAY['sufism','fana','mysticism','islam','rumi']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',1,5,
'The Kabbalistic Tree of Life consists of ten sefirot representing:',
'["The ten attributes or emanations through which the Infinite (Ein Sof) reveals itself and creates all reality","The ten stages of purification through which the soul passes after death","The ten commandments given to Moses encoded in divine symbolic form","Ten angelic hierarchies arranged in a ladder between earth and the divine throne"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Tree of Life is Kabbalahs central symbolic map, ten sefirot arranged in a specific pattern connected by 22 paths. The sefirot represent ten attributes or dimensions through which the unknowable Ein Sof progressively reveals and limits itself to create the universe. From Keter (Crown) through Chokhmah (Wisdom) Binah (Understanding) and the remaining seven the Tree maps the divine creative process.',
'The Tree of Life is one of the most comprehensive symbolic systems ever developed, applied to cosmology psychology ethics mystical experience biblical interpretation and ritual magic. Its 22 paths correspond to the 22 letters of the Hebrew alphabet and the 22 Major Arcana of the Tarot. The convergence of Kabbalah Hebrew letters and Tarot created one of the most richly layered symbolic languages in Western mystical tradition.',
'Kabbalah Tree of Life Jewish mysticism sefirot sacred ancient',ARRAY['kabbalah','tree of life','sefirot','jewish mysticism','ein sof']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',4,15,
'The perennial philosophy (philosophia perennis) described by Aldous Huxley proposes that:',
'["All the worlds mystical traditions share a common core of metaphysical truth about the nature of consciousness and ultimate reality","Religious traditions are culturally determined projections of universal psychological needs rather than responses to external transcendent reality","Eastern religions are philosophically superior to Western ones due to their focus on inner experience over external doctrine","Religion and science share the same underlying epistemology, both are empirical investigations of different aspects of reality"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Huxleys 1945 book documented a common metaphysical framework across Hindu Vedanta Buddhist Mahayana Christian mysticism Islamic Sufism Taoism and indigenous traditions. The core: reality is ultimately a divine Ground; humans have the capacity to identify with this Ground; recognising this identity is the highest human purpose; the path involves ego-transcendence ethical purification and contemplative practice.',
'The fundamental question the perennial philosophy poses: is the remarkable convergence of mystical experience across all cultures evidence that mystics are contacting the same genuine reality? Or is it convergent cognitive responses to similar contemplative practices? The question remains open and is perhaps the most important empirical question in the study of consciousness.',
'world religions unity mysticism philosophy light enlightenment globe',ARRAY['perennial philosophy','huxley','mysticism','comparative religion']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',4,15,
'Meister Eckhart 14th-century Dominican mystic was condemned by the Pope for teaching:',
'["The identity of the soul with God in the Godhead, that the ground of the soul and the Ground of God are identical","That Jesus was not historically real, that the Christ is solely an inner spiritual reality","That salvation could be achieved without the Church through direct mystical experience alone","That matter is divine, a form of pantheism denying Gods transcendence"]',
0,'historical',
'Eckharts condemned propositions centred on his teaching about the Grunt (ground or foundation), the deepest level of both God and the soul. He taught that in the Grunt God and the soul are identical. The eye through which I see God is the same eye through which God sees me. This was condemned as heretical (Papal bull In Agro Dominico 1329) though some Catholic thinkers today consider the condemnation historically contingent rather than doctrinally necessary.',
'Eckharts thought stands as perhaps the most radical expression of Christian mysticism ever formulated in orthodox theological language. His statement The eye through which I see God is the same eye through which God sees me is structurally identical to the Advaita teaching Tat tvam asi. The Catholic Church condemning its own most profound mystic for teaching what Hindu Vedanta and Buddhist Prajnaparamita teach openly reveals the profound tension between mystical experience and institutional religion.',
'medieval Christian mysticism cathedral Europe gothic church ancient',ARRAY['Meister Eckhart','Christian mysticism','ground of soul','medieval']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',12,50,
'The Islamic concept of tawhid and the Sufi concept of wahdat al-wujud differ in that:',
'["Tawhid affirms Gods absolute oneness (monotheism) while wahdat al-wujud (Ibn Arabis Unity of Being) declares that all existence is a manifestation of God, a mystical monism","Tawhid is an exoteric doctrine for ordinary believers while wahdat al-wujud is the esoteric core known only to initiates","Tawhid applies to Gods transcendence while wahdat al-wujud applies to Gods immanence, both are orthodox Islam","They are identical, wahdat al-wujud is simply the philosophical formulation of the Quranic declaration There is no God but God"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Tawhid (divine unity) is the central doctrine of Islamic theology, the absolute oneness of God distinguished from all creation. Ibn Arabi (1165-1240 CE) developed wahdat al-wujud (Unity of Being), the radical mystical position that there is only one Being and all apparently distinct entities are manifestations of that one Being. While tawhid maintains a distinction between Creator and creation wahdat al-wujud collapses this distinction.',
'Ibn Arabis wahdat al-wujud represents perhaps the most sophisticated philosophical system produced by any Islamic thinker, a vast internally consistent ontology in which God is both the Absolute Hidden (unknown in Himself) and the manifest world (known through the self-disclosure of His names and attributes). The system maps almost perfectly onto Advaita Vedanta while emerging entirely from within the Islamic Quranic tradition.',
'Islamic mysticism Sufi mosque ancient arabesque spiritual geometry',ARRAY['tawhid','wahdat al wujud','ibn arabi','sufism','unity of being']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',12,50,
'Zoroastrianisms theological innovation which directly influenced Judaism Christianity and Islam was:',
'["Ethical dualism, the cosmos is a battlefield between Ahura Mazda (Wise Lord) and Angra Mainyu (Destructive Spirit), individual humans must choose sides","Absolute monotheism, before Zoroaster all Middle Eastern religions were polytheistic","The concept of divine judgment after death, Egyptian mythology is the only other ancient source for this idea","The idea that a divine saviour (Saoshyant) would come at the end of time to resurrect the dead and restore paradise"]',
0,'historical',
'Zoroastrianism (founded approximately 1500-1000 BCE) was among the first religions to systematically develop ethical monotheism and cosmic dualism, a good God (Ahura Mazda) opposed by an evil spirit (Angra Mainyu) with humans as free agents whose moral choices affect the cosmic battle. Through the Babylonian exile (597-539 BCE) these concepts, the devil apocalypse resurrection final judgment heaven and hell as moral destinations, entered Jewish theology and subsequently Christianity and Islam.',
'The influence of Zoroastrianism on Western religion is one of the most underappreciated stories in religious history. The concepts that feel most essential to Christianity, Satan as a cosmic adversary the resurrection of the dead a final judgment a messianic saviour, all have their clearest pre-Christian articulation in Zoroastrian texts. When the Three Wise Men (Magi) followed the star to Bethlehem they were likely Zoroastrian priests, the tradition that announced Christ had its roots in the oldest dualistic religion in the world.',
'Zoroaster ancient Persia fire temple Ahura Mazda',ARRAY['zoroastrianism','ahura mazda','dualism','ancient persia']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',1,5,
'The Jewish concept of Tikkun Olam (repair of the world) in Kabbalistic tradition refers to:',
'["The cosmic process of gathering scattered divine sparks (nitzotzot) that fell into matter during the breaking of the divine vessels and restoring them to their source","A social justice mandate requiring Jews to work for human rights and equality in the external world","The daily prayer practice believed to maintain the cosmic order","The process of healing the divine feminine (Shekhinah) from her exile by performing the 613 commandments"]',
0,'esoteric',
'In Lurianic Kabbalah (Isaac Luria 16th-century Safed) tikkun olam has a specific cosmic meaning: during the primordial creation the divine light was too intense for the vessels (sefirot) causing the Shevirat HaKelim (Breaking of the Vessels). Divine sparks (nitzotzot) fell into the material world trapped in shells (kelipot). Every human act done with sacred intention helps gather these sparks and restore them to their divine source.',
'Lurias myth of the Breaking of the Vessels and the scattered sparks is one of the most psychologically resonant cosmic narratives ever developed. It answers the question of why the world contains suffering and evil not with human sin but with a cosmic accident, and places the responsibility for repair not on God but on each human being. Every mundane act performed with consciousness participates in the healing of the cosmos.',
'Kabbalah Jewish mysticism divine sparks repair world cosmic healing',ARRAY['tikkun olam','kabbalah','lurianic kabbalah','divine sparks']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',4,15,
'What distinguishes mystical experience across traditions according to comparative religion scholars like William James?',
'["Four common qualities: ineffability (cannot be adequately described in words) noetic quality (it feels like genuine knowledge) transiency (it does not last) and passivity (the person feels acted upon not acting)","The experience is always terrifying, the mysterium tremendum, before it becomes rapturous and joyful","Mystical experience always involves the dissolution of personal identity and cannot be distinguished across traditions","The experiences are entirely culturally conditioned and have no common features, what seems common is projection of shared Westernised academic expectations"]',
0,'philosophical',
'William James in The Varieties of Religious Experience (1902) identified four marks of mystical experience across traditions: ineffability (mystical states cannot be adequately expressed in words, they must be directly experienced) noetic quality (they carry a sense of profound insight into truth about reality) transiency (they do not last though their effects may) and passivity (the person feels their own will is in abeyance as if seized by a greater power).',
'James four marks of mystical experience remain one of the most useful analytical tools in the study of consciousness despite being over 120 years old. The fact that mystics in every culture and historical period report experiences with these four common features, despite radically different doctrinal contexts, is the strongest empirical argument for the perennial philosophy. The experiences may be interpreted differently but the phenomenological structure is remarkably consistent.',
'mystical experience meditation prayer light consciousness spiritual',ARRAY['william james','mystical experience','ineffability','noetic','comparative religion']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',12,50,
'The Buddhist concept of sunyata (emptiness) and the Taoist concept of wu (nothingness) share what deeper philosophical insight?',
'["Both point to the absence of inherent self-sufficient existence in all phenomena, things exist only in relationship interdependence and process rather than as fixed self-contained entities","Both teach that the material world is a complete illusion with no reality whatsoever, only consciousness exists","Both describe the divine source as a void or nothing from which all things emerge and to which all things return","Both are nihilistic philosophies that deny the value of existence and the possibility of genuine meaning or purpose"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Sunyata in Buddhism (especially Madhyamaka philosophy of Nagarjuna) means that all phenomena are empty of inherent self-sufficient existence, they arise in dependence on causes conditions and conceptual designation. Nothing exists from its own side. The Taoist wu (nothingness) similarly points to the inexhaustible generative emptiness at the root of all phenomena, the void that is paradoxically more full than anything manifest.',
'The sunyata-wu parallel is one of the deepest convergences in world philosophy. Both traditions arrived through completely different analytical methods (Buddhist logic and Taoist contemplative poetry) at the same insight: the most real thing is not any particular thing but the open dynamic relational field from which all things emerge. This is neither nihilism (things dont exist) nor naive realism (things exist as fixed entities) but something more subtle: things exist as dynamic patterns in an open field of relationship.',
'Buddhist emptiness sunyata Taoism nothingness philosophy East',ARRAY['sunyata','emptiness','buddhism','taoism','nothingness']),

-- REALM 10: HIDDEN HISTORY (10 questions)
(10,'Hidden History',1,5,
'In which dialogues of Plato does the story of Atlantis appear and who describes it?',
'["Timaeus and Critias, told by Critias who claims it came from Solon via Egyptian priests","The Republic and the Phaedrus, described by Socrates as an ancient memory of his soul","The Symposium and the Phaedo, recounted by Diotima as a historical precedent for philosophical ascent","The Laws and the Statesman, told by the Athenian Stranger as a warning about hubris"]',
0,'historical',
'Plato introduced the Atlantis narrative in Timaeus and Critias (c. 360 BCE). The story is attributed to Critias who claims to have learned it from his grandfather Critias the Elder who heard it from Solon who was told by Egyptian priests at Sais. The priests reportedly told Solon that Atlantis was destroyed 9000 years before Solons time (approximately 9600 BCE) by earthquakes and floods in a single day and night.',
'The transmission chain in Platos account (Egyptian priests → Solon → Critias the Elder → Critias the Younger → Plato) has been cited as both evidence of the storys historical basis and as grounds for skepticism. Egyptian priests were custodians of records spanning millennia, they told Solon that the Greeks were children compared to Egypts historical memory. Whether Plato created Atlantis as a philosophical allegory preserved a genuine historical memory or some combination remains one of scholarships most enduring debates.',
'Plato ancient Greece scroll philosophy Atlantis ocean map',ARRAY['atlantis','plato','timaeus','critias','ancient history']),

(10,'Hidden History',1,5,
'The Younger Dryas Impact Hypothesis (YDIH) proposes that approximately 12800 years ago:',
'["A cosmic impact event (fragmenting comet or asteroid) triggered a rapid climate cooling that may have ended an earlier advanced civilisation","A supervolcano eruption at Yellowstone caused a millennium-long winter wiping out megafauna","Melting of the Laurentide Ice Sheet caused a catastrophic flood depositing the Younger Dryas sediment layer","A pole shift displaced Earths rotational axis causing the sudden extinction of mammoths and other megafauna"]',
0,'speculative',
'The YDIH (proposed by Firestone et al. 2007) suggests a fragmenting cosmic object impacted or airburst over North America approximately 12800 years ago triggering the Younger Dryas cold period (sudden temperature drop lasting approximately 1300 years). Evidence cited includes: a platinum-rich black mat layer in archaeological sites across multiple continents nano-diamonds formed by cosmic impacts spherules and the extinction of North American megafauna.',
'The YDIH is significant for esoteric history because it provides a potentially scientific mechanism for a real global catastrophe at approximately the time Plato placed Atlantiss destruction (9000 years before Solon approximately 9600 BCE, close to 12800 BCE). If a catastrophic impact event ended an earlier advanced civilisation and was encoded in human collective memory as flood myths (which appear in virtually every culture on Earth) the mythological record becomes potential historical testimony.',
'comet impact ancient catastrophe ice age meteorite Earth crater',ARRAY['younger dryas','impact hypothesis','ancient catastrophe','comet']),

(10,'Hidden History',4,15,
'Graham Hancocks central thesis argues that:',
'["An advanced civilisation was destroyed approximately 12000 years ago and its survivors seeded subsequent civilisations with astronomy architecture and spiritual knowledge","Ancient megaliths like the pyramids were built by extraterrestrial beings whose technology was lost when they departed","Ancient peoples were connected by a worldwide ocean-going civilisation sharing knowledge from a fixed golden age","The ancient world was unified under a single global empire whose capital was in Antarctica"]',
0,'speculative',
'Hancock argues (in Fingerprints of the Gods Magicians of the Gods America Before) that geological and archaeological evidence points to a lost civilisation of high sophistication that existed during the last Ice Age and was destroyed by a cosmic catastrophe approximately 12800 years ago. Survivors transmitted astronomical architectural and spiritual knowledge to the emerging post-catastrophe cultures of Egypt Sumer and Mesoamerica.',
'Hancocks work sits at the interesting boundary between alternative archaeology and mainstream science. His core challenge, that civilisation may be older and more developed than currently acknowledged, has gained some mainstream traction particularly as evidence for the YDIH has accumulated and as sites like Gobekli Tepe have demonstrated complex culture far earlier than previously accepted.',
'ancient ruins archaeology stone pyramid mystery civilisation jungle',ARRAY['graham hancock','lost civilisation','ancient history','fingerprints of gods']),

(10,'Hidden History',4,15,
'The megalithic stones at Baalbek in Lebanon are considered anomalous because:',
'["They include quarried limestone blocks weighing 800-1000 metric tons, far exceeding the capabilities of any confirmed ancient engineering technology","They contain inscriptions in a pre-Phoenician script that has never been deciphered","They were quarried and then abandoned mid-project suggesting the builders lost their technology suddenly","Their precise dimensions encode advanced astronomical knowledge to 5 significant figures"]',
0,'empirical',
'The Baalbek platform includes limestone blocks weighing 800-1000 metric tons, the heaviest known quarried stones in the world. The heaviest stones in the Great Pyramid weigh approximately 80 metric tons; the Baalbek blocks are 8-12 times heavier. No crane technology in the ancient or modern world can lift a 1000-ton stone without purpose-built equipment. How stones of this size were quarried transported and placed with precision remains genuinely unexplained.',
'Baalbek represents one of the most concrete anomalies in ancient engineering. This is not mythology or interpretation, it is a physical fact in Lebanon. The Romans despite their advanced engineering did not quarry stones of this size, suggesting these blocks are from a pre-Roman construction. What civilisation quarried these stones when and why remains genuinely unknown to mainstream archaeology.',
'Baalbek Lebanon ancient stone temple Roman ruins massive block',ARRAY['baalbek','ancient engineering','mystery','lebanon','megaliths']),

(10,'Hidden History',12,50,
'Robert Schochs geological analysis of the Great Sphinx at Giza controversially proposed that:',
'["The Sphinxs weathering pattern indicates water erosion from heavy rainfall, suggesting construction before 7000 BCE far earlier than the Egyptian Old Kingdom","The Sphinx was built by the Atlantean civilisation as a marker pointing to the Hall of Records beneath its paws","The Sphinx was originally a natural rock formation carved by the Nile into a lion shape and later adapted by Old Kingdom Egyptians","The Sphinxs body shows evidence of ancient repairs using materials not available in Egypt, suggesting it was transported from elsewhere"]',
0,'speculative',
'Geologist Robert Schoch (Boston University) presented his analysis at the 1991 Geological Society of America conference arguing that the deep horizontal erosion patterns on the Sphinxs body are consistent with water weathering from heavy rainfall, not wind and sand erosion. The Sahara region had significant rainfall before approximately 5000-7000 BCE. This would place the Sphinxs original construction thousands of years before the conventional date of c. 2500 BCE.',
'Schochs geological analysis is methodologically mainstream, he applied standard geological weathering analysis to the Sphinxs limestone. What is controversial is the implication: a monument of this sophistication before 7000+ BCE challenges the conventional timeline of human civilisation. The geological evidence does not itself answer what civilisation built it, it only establishes a date incompatible with the conventional attribution.',
'Great Sphinx Giza Egypt ancient erosion geology mystery',ARRAY['sphinx','schoch','water erosion','ancient egypt','giza']),

(10,'Hidden History',12,50,
'The Book of Enoch excluded from the biblical canon describes:',
'["The Watchers, fallen angels who descended to Earth mated with human women producing giant offspring (Nephilim) and taught humanity forbidden knowledge","The creation of the world in seven days from the perspective of angels who witnessed it","The complete history of all biblical patriarchs before and after the Flood in expanded narrative form","The cosmological architecture of heaven, the seven heavens their angelic inhabitants and the divine throne room"]',
0,'historical',
'The Book of Enoch (1st Enoch) preserved complete only in Ethiopian Christianity but quoted in the New Testament (Jude 1:14-15) describes the Watchers, angels who descended to Mount Hermon took human women as wives and produced giant offspring (the Nephilim mentioned in Genesis 6:1-4). The Watchers also taught humanity various arts: metalworking cosmetics herb lore astrology and the making of weapons, considered forbidden knowledge.',
'The Book of Enoch was widely read in the Second Temple period and directly influenced the New Testament yet was excluded from the biblical canon. The Watcher tradition, divine beings who interfered with humanity sharing forbidden technology and producing hybrid offspring, appears across ancient Near Eastern mythology. The Sumerian Anunnaki who descended from heaven the Greek Titans who warred with the Olympians and the Nephilim of Genesis all share structural similarities suggesting a common ancient narrative about supernatural interference in human development.',
'ancient scroll Book of Enoch Watchers Nephilim angels fallen',ARRAY['book of enoch','watchers','nephilim','fallen angels','ancient texts']),

(10,'Hidden History',4,15,
'The ancient Vedic text Mahabharata describes flying vehicles called vimanas and weapons called brahmastra that researchers compare to:',
'["Nuclear weapons and aircraft, descriptions of enormous explosions that turn sand to glass and symptoms matching radiation sickness","Metaphorical descriptions of spiritual powers (siddhis) developed through intense yogic practice","Allegorical representations of weather phenomena, vimanas as clouds brahmastra as lightning","Actual mechanical devices powered by mercury vortex engines confirmed by recent archaeological excavations"]',
0,'speculative',
'The Mahabharata and Ramayana contain detailed descriptions of vimanas (flying machines or divine vehicles) and weapons of mass destruction. The brahmastra is described as a single projectile charged with all the power of the Universe that reduced to ashes the entire race. At Mohenjo-daro archaeologists found evidence of what appears to be an ancient explosion with vitrified sand (turned to glass by extreme heat) similar to nuclear test sites.',
'The descriptions of brahmastra and the archaeological evidence at Mohenjo-daro remain genuinely contested, mainstream archaeology attributes the vitrified layer to other causes while alternative researchers point to the descriptions remarkable specificity. Whether ancient India possessed or imagined advanced weapons or whether these texts encode real historical memories of a forgotten technology the question touches on the fundamental assumption that technological sophistication can only move in one direction from primitive to advanced.',
'ancient India Vedic temple vimana Sanskrit manuscript mythology',ARRAY['vimana','brahmastra','mahabharata','ancient india','vedic']),

(10,'Hidden History',1,5,
'The Piri Reis map discovered in 1929 is considered anomalous because:',
'["It appears to show Antarctica with an ice-free coastline as it would have looked before approximately 4000 BCE before the ice cap formed","It uses a projection system identical to modern satellite mapping suggesting the use of aerial observation","It shows the Americas drawn to the same scale as Europe and Africa suggesting 15th-century contact before Columbus","It contains navigational instructions in a language that predates any known writing system by 5000 years"]',
0,'speculative',
'The Piri Reis map (1513 CE) is an Ottoman Turkish map compiled by admiral Piri Reis from older source maps. Charles Hapgood proposed in Maps of the Ancient Sea Kings (1966) that the southern coastline depicted appears to show Antarctica with an ice-free coastline as it would have appeared before the ice sheet formed approximately 4000-6000 BCE, thousands of years before Antarctica was officially discovered in 1820. This would suggest the existence of ancient maps predating known civilisation.',
'The Piri Reis map remains genuinely debated. Mainstream cartographers argue the coastline represents a misidentified South America or Terra Australis Incognita (a hypothetical southern continent). Alternative researchers maintain the ice-free Antarctic coastline match is too specific to be coincidental, implying the existence of an advanced ancient seafaring civilisation with accurate surveying technology. The map is a genuine anomaly whose resolution depends on which interpretation of the ambiguous coastline one finds more compelling.',
'Piri Reis ancient map Antarctica coastline mystery cartography',ARRAY['piri reis','ancient maps','antarctica','anomalous cartography','hapgood']),

(10,'Hidden History',12,50,
'What is the Sphinx Water Erosion Hypothesis and why is it controversial?',
'["It proposes that the Sphinx was carved before 7000 BCE based on geological evidence of water erosion from rainfall suggesting it predates known Egyptian civilisation by millennia","It proposes that the Sphinx was originally a water deity whose form was changed from a crocodile to a lion by Khafre around 2500 BCE","It proposes that the Sphinx was transported from elsewhere by the Atlanteans leaving water erosion marks from ocean submersion","It proposes that the Sphinx originally faced east toward a now-sunken harbour city explaining the water erosion patterns"]',
0,'speculative',
'The Sphinx Water Erosion Hypothesis (John Anthony West and Robert Schoch 1991) proposes that the weathering patterns on the Sphinx body, deep vertical fissures and rounded erosion profiles, are consistent with water erosion from heavy rainfall rather than wind and sand erosion. Since the last period of significant rainfall in the Sahara region ended approximately 5000-7000 BCE this would place the Sphinxs original construction before that date, thousands of years before the conventional attribution to Khafre (c. 2500 BCE).',
'The mainstream Egyptological response to the water erosion hypothesis is that the erosion patterns are consistent with wind erosion over a long enough period and that no civilisation sophisticated enough to carve the Sphinx is known to have existed in Egypt before 5000-7000 BCE. Schoch responds that the geological evidence for water erosion is clear and that absence of evidence for the earlier civilisation may simply reflect the lack of archaeological investigation rather than the absence of the civilisation. This is precisely the kind of anomaly that cannot be resolved by existing evidence alone.',
'Great Sphinx Giza Egypt ancient water erosion geology',ARRAY['sphinx','water erosion hypothesis','john anthony west','schoch','giza']),

-- REALM 11: SYMBOLISM (10 questions)
(11,'Symbolism',1,5,
'In the Tarot''s Major Arcana The Fool (card 0) represents:',
'["Pure unlimited potential at the beginning of the Heros journey, the soul before it takes on the limitations of experience","Stupidity recklessness and the folly of spiritual seekers who pursue esoteric knowledge","A specific historical figure, the court jester who spoke truth to power in medieval courts","The final state of enlightenment, the return to divine innocence after completing the spiritual path"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Fool depicts a young figure about to step off a cliff with a pack on a staff and a white rose in hand. It represents the soul at the beginning of its journey, pure potential divine innocence and unlimited possibility. The dog at his heels represents the voice of worldly wisdom trying to hold him back. The cliff represents the leap of faith required to begin any genuine journey.',
'The Fools position as card 0 (before numbered existence begins) and sometimes card XXII (after the World completes the cycle) reveals its double significance: it is both beginning and end alpha and omega of the souls journey. The Fool who ends the journey is not the same as the Fool who began it, the second Fool has been through all 21 cards and returned to the infinite freedom of 0 but now consciously. This is the Zen beginners mind in its deepest form.',
'Tarot Fool card spiritual journey mystical symbolic art',ARRAY['tarot','major arcana','the fool','symbolism','archetypes']),

(11,'Symbolism',1,5,
'The Flower of Life is a geometric figure that:',
'["Contains 19 overlapping circles in a hexagonal pattern from which Metatrons Cube and all five Platonic solids can be derived","Consists of a spiral of Fibonacci circles expanding outward from a central point","Contains 64 tetrahedra arranged in a cube, the building block of the unified field","Encodes the complete astrological chart geometrically, all 12 zodiacal positions"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Flower of Life consists of 19 complete circles in a hexagonal pattern. Within it sacred geometers identify the Seed of Life (7 circles) the Egg of Life and the Fruit of Life (13 circles). From the Fruit of Life connecting the centres with lines produces Metatrons Cube, a figure containing all five Platonic solids. The figure appears in ancient Egypt Assyria Buddhist temples across Asia and medieval Europe.',
'The worldwide appearance of the Flower of Life across cultures with no known historical contact is one of sacred geometrys most compelling mysteries. Its mathematical properties are genuinely remarkable, it encodes the Golden Ratio the Platonic solids and fundamental wave interference patterns. Whether ancient peoples discovered these properties independently shared them through lost contact or accessed them through direct geometric perception remains unknown.',
'Flower of Life sacred geometry ancient pattern hexagonal circle',ARRAY['flower of life','sacred geometry','metatrons cube','ancient symbol']),

(11,'Symbolism',4,15,
'The Ouroboros, the serpent eating its own tail, appears across cultures and universally symbolises:',
'["Eternal cyclical return self-referential infinity and the unity of all opposites, the self-contained wholeness of the universe","Death and rebirth, the serpent must die (losing its tail) before it can be reborn (regrowing the tail)","The primal chaos from which the universe emerged, the formless before the first act of creation","Time as a linear progression that curves back on itself, the universes ultimate fate of cyclical collapse and re-creation"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Ouroboros (Greek: tail-devourer) represents self-referential wholeness, a system that contains and generates itself. It appears in the Egyptian Book of the Dead Gnostic texts Viking mythology as Jormungandr alchemical manuscripts and Hindu iconography. Jung interpreted it as a symbol of the collective unconscious. Chemist August Kekule reported dreaming of an Ouroboros in 1865, which revealed to him the ring structure of benzene.',
'The Ouroboros encodes a deep mathematical truth: self-reference and self-containment are fundamental features of both consciousness and certain mathematical systems. Godels incompleteness theorem demonstrated that any sufficiently complex formal system contains statements that refer to the system itself, a logical Ouroboros. The universe as a closed causal loop is an Ouroboros at the cosmological scale. Ancient symbol modern mathematics and cosmology converge in the same figure.',
'Ouroboros serpent infinity ancient Egypt alchemy symbol circle',ARRAY['ouroboros','alchemy','symbol','infinity','serpent']),

(11,'Symbolism',4,15,
'In the Tarot The Tower (card XVI) most accurately represents:',
'["The sudden violent collapse of false structures and ego-based certainties, painful but ultimately liberating","The destructive power of human ambition, the Tower of Babel as a warning against overreaching","Military defeat and the end of political power","The dark night of the soul, the extended period of spiritual desolation before dawn"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Tower depicts a tall tower struck by lightning with figures falling from its heights. It represents the sudden catastrophic collapse of structures built on false foundations, whether beliefs relationships identities or worldly achievements. The lightning bolt is divine force, not malevolent but illuminating exposing the false. What the Tower destroys was already structurally unsound; the destruction however painful is a precondition for building something true.',
'The Tower is perhaps the most feared card in a Tarot reading yet carries a deeply liberating truth: the things we cling to most desperately are often the very things that imprison us. The Tower does not destroy truth, it destroys the illusion of permanence and security we build around temporary structures. After every Tower moment there is the opportunity to build something more honest more resilient and more aligned with reality.',
'Tower tarot lightning symbolic art spiritual crisis transformation',ARRAY['tarot','the tower','major arcana','transformation','crisis']),

(11,'Symbolism',12,50,
'In alchemy the four stages of the Great Work (Magnum Opus) and their colours are:',
'["Nigredo (black) → Albedo (white) → Citrinitas (yellow) → Rubedo (red), death purification dawn and completion","Prima Materia (red) → Solutio (blue) → Coagulatio (white) → Calcinatio (gold)","Mortificatio (black) → Separatio (white) → Coniunctio (red) → Multiplicatio (gold)","Calcination (red) → Dissolution (blue) → Separation (white) → Conjunction (black)"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Great Works stages describe both laboratory alchemy and psychological-spiritual transformation. Nigredo: dissolution and death, confronting the shadow the dark night of the soul. Albedo: purification, the silver Moon stage emergence of the anima/animus. Citrinitas: the transitional yellowing first light of dawn. Rubedo: reddening, final transmutation into gold the philosophers stone individuation completed.',
'Jung devoted years to alchemical texts precisely because he found in the alchemists symbolic language the most precise pre-scientific description of the individuation process he had ever encountered. When lead becomes gold in alchemy the ego becomes Self; when the impure metal is purified the shadow is integrated. Ancient chemistry and modern depth psychology are secretly the same pursuit, the alchemists were doing genuine inner work while believing they were transforming metals.',
'alchemy laboratory medieval gold transformation stages mystical',ARRAY['alchemy','great work','nigredo','rubedo','transformation']),

(11,'Symbolism',12,50,
'The number 7 appears with remarkable frequency across unrelated ancient traditions. Which connection is factually accurate?',
'["Seven chakras seven Hermetic Principles seven days of creation seven classical planets seven musical notes seven colours of visible light, suggesting an underlying structural principle","Seven was chosen arbitrarily by different cultures as their sacred number and the similarity is coincidental","Seven represents the number of wounds of Christ and all other sevens derive from Christian influence on world culture","The number seven appears in nature (seven continents seven seas) leading cultures to adopt it symbolically"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The frequency of the number 7 across independent ancient traditions is genuinely remarkable: 7 chakras in the Hindu/yogic system 7 Hermetic Principles 7 classical planets known to the ancient world 7 days of the week named after these planets 7 notes of the diatonic musical scale 7 colours of visible light (ROY G BIV) 7 days of the Genesis creation 7 sacraments in Catholicism 7 seals in Revelation.',
'The ubiquity of 7 suggests it may reflect something fundamental about how reality organises itself rather than being an arbitrary cultural choice. The 7 classical planets ordered the ancient cosmos; the 7 notes of the musical scale divide the octave in the most natural way; the 7 chakras map to major nerve plexuses of the human body. Whether coincidence universal archetypical resonance or evidence of a common ancient source of knowledge this convergence is one of sacred geometrys most enduring questions.',
'sacred number seven mystical symbols cosmic pattern sacred geometry',ARRAY['sacred numbers','seven','numerology','symbolism','patterns']),

(11,'Symbolism',1,5,
'The Tarot''s Major Arcana card The World (card XXI) represents:',
'["Completion wholeness and the successful integration of all experiences, the souls triumphant return to the beginning transformed","Death, the end of the physical world and the souls judgment before the divine throne","The material world as illusion, a reminder to release attachment to earthly things","Cosmic consciousness, the mystics final dissolution of self into the infinite"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The World (or The Universe) depicts a dancing figure at the centre of a laurel wreath surrounded by the four fixed signs of the zodiac, the same four beings appearing in Ezekiels vision and in Revelation. The dancing figure represents the soul that has successfully integrated all aspects of the psyche represented by the previous 20 cards, having descended into the underworld faced death transformed through alchemical fire and achieved wholeness.',
'The World card stands as the ultimate promise of the Tarot system: that the long journey through all the experiences of life, including its darkest and most challenging cards, leads not to destruction but to completion. The dancer at the centre is the individuated Self the Atman recognised as Brahman the pneuma returned to the Pleroma. Every Major Arcana card encountered was a necessary station on this journey.',
'Tarot World card completion wholeness mystical spiritual art',ARRAY['tarot','the world','major arcana','completion','wholeness']),

(11,'Symbolism',4,15,
'Sacred geometry proposes that certain geometric forms encode fundamental truths about reality. Which claim has the strongest empirical support?',
'["The Golden Ratio (phi) and Fibonacci sequence appear throughout natural growth patterns in plants animals and galaxies with mathematical precision, genuinely empirically verified","The Platonic solids (tetrahedron cube octahedron dodecahedron icosahedron) are the basic building blocks of all matter as Plato proposed in the Timaeus","Cymatic patterns (shapes formed by sound vibrations in a medium) exactly match the sacred geometry patterns found in all ancient religious architecture, proving sound created these forms","Certain geometric proportions have verifiable effects on human consciousness, exposure to golden ratio proportions consistently reduces cortisol and increases feelings of wellbeing"]',
0,'empirical',
'The empirical status of different sacred geometry claims varies considerably. The most solidly verified: the Golden Ratio and Fibonacci sequence genuinely appear throughout natural growth patterns, in phyllotaxis (leaf and petal arrangements) nautilus shells animal body proportions and galaxy spiral arms. This is confirmed mathematics not speculation. The Platonic solids as elementary particle shapes and cymatic claims for ancient architecture are more controversial with much weaker empirical support.',
'The distinction between empirically verified sacred geometry (Golden Ratio in nature) and more speculative claims (Platonic solids as elementary particles consciousness effects of geometric proportions) is precisely the kind of epistemic discernment the AetherMind Discernment Score aims to develop. Sacred geometry contains a spectrum from genuine mathematical insight to wishful interpretation, and the ability to distinguish them is itself a form of wisdom.',
'sacred geometry mathematics golden ratio nature patterns',ARRAY['sacred geometry','golden ratio','fibonacci','empirical','patterns']),

(11,'Symbolism',12,50,
'The Major Arcana of the Tarot is often mapped onto the Kabbalistic Tree of Life. What is the significance of this correspondence?',
'["It suggests both systems are mapping the same underlying structure of consciousness and the soul''s journey, 22 paths of the Tree correspond to 22 Major Arcana creating a unified map of spiritual evolution","It proves that both systems were created by the same secret society (the Order of the Golden Dawn) who deliberately designed them to fit together","It shows that medieval Jewish mystics were familiar with Tarot cards and incorporated them into their cosmological system","It is coincidental, the 22 number match was noticed by 18th-century occultists who retroactively forced a correspondence that does not hold up to scrutiny"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Hermetic Order of the Golden Dawn (late 19th century) systematised the correspondence between the 22 Hebrew letters the 22 paths of the Kabbalistic Tree of Life and the 22 Major Arcana of the Tarot. The major arcana are assigned to the paths between the sefirot allowing the Tarot to serve as a map of spiritual states corresponding to each level of the Tree. The system was further developed by Aleister Crowley (Thoth Tarot) and Paul Foster Case (BOTA Tarot).',
'The Tarot-Kabbalah correspondence represents one of the most ambitious synthetic systems in Western esotericism: the attempt to create a unified map of consciousness using Hebrew letters as the fundamental symbolic alphabet Kabbalistic cosmology as the structural framework and Tarot imagery as the visual language. Whether the correspondence reveals a genuine underlying structural unity or is an impressive intellectual construction imposed on two unrelated systems is a perennial debate in the study of Western esotericism.',
'Kabbalah Tree of Life Tarot Hebrew letters sacred symbols esoteric',ARRAY['tarot','kabbalah','tree of life','22 paths','golden dawn']),

(11,'Symbolism',4,15,
'What is the difference between an archetype and a symbol in Jungian psychology?',
'["Archetypes are universal structural patterns in the collective unconscious (the hero the shadow the trickster); symbols are the specific images through which archetypes manifest in a particular cultural context","Archetypes are conscious cultural constructions while symbols are unconscious eruptions from the collective psyche","Archetypes are personal to each individual while symbols are universal, shared across all cultures and historical periods","Archetypes are the negative shadow aspects of the psyche while symbols are the positive expressions of the same energy"]',
0,'philosophical',
'In Jungian psychology archetypes are the structural patterns or tendencies in the collective unconscious, predispositions to experience certain patterns of emotion image and behaviour (the hero the great mother the trickster the self). Archetypes themselves are not directly visible, they manifest through symbols: the specific images stories and figures that carry archetypal energy in a particular cultural context. The same archetype (the hero) manifests differently as Odysseus Gilgamesh Superman or Harry Potter.',
'The distinction between archetype (universal structural pattern) and symbol (its specific cultural manifestation) allows Jungian psychology to simultaneously affirm universal human psychological patterns and the diversity of cultural expression. The hero archetype is universal; the specific form the hero takes is cultural. This framework resolves the apparent paradox of how all humans can share the same deep psychology while expressing it through radically different mythological religious and artistic traditions.',
'Jung archetypes symbols psychology collective unconscious universal',ARRAY['jung','archetypes','symbols','psychology','collective unconscious']),

-- REALM 12: ETHICS AND WISDOM (10 questions)
(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',1,5,
'The unexamined life is not worth living, in what context did Socrates make this statement?',
'["At his trial in 399 BCE defending his philosophical practice even as he faced the death penalty","In a dialogue with Meno about whether virtue can be taught","When speaking to young Athenians who wished to join his philosophical circle","In his final conversation with friends on the day of his execution"]',
0,'historical',
'Socrates made this declaration at his trial in 399 BCE as recorded in Platos Apology. Facing charges of impiety and corrupting the youth of Athens Socrates refused to abandon philosophical practice even to save his life. When offered exile or silence he declined, the practice of examining himself and others was identical with living as a human being. He was convicted and chose death by hemlock.',
'Socrates choice of death over the abandonment of philosophy has shaped Western ethical thought for 2400 years. For Socrates philosophy was not an academic discipline but a way of being, a practice of honest self-examination and genuine conversation that constituted the most fully human life possible. The statement was made not in a classroom but in a courtroom by a man who had written nothing facing execution, the ultimate test of whether the examined life was genuinely worth living.',
'Socrates ancient Athens philosophy trial hemlock Greece',ARRAY['socrates','apology','philosophy','examined life','ethics']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',1,5,
'The Stoic dichotomy of control (Epictetus) teaches that:',
'["Freedom comes from focusing exclusively on what is up to us (thoughts intentions responses) and accepting everything else with equanimity","We should control all aspects of our environment to achieve the conditions for virtue","Both external circumstances and internal states can be controlled through sufficient willpower","The wise person achieves emotional control by suppressing feelings through rational effort"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Epictetus opens the Enchiridion with the fundamental Stoic distinction: some things are up to us (our judgments impulses desires and aversions) and some things are not up to us (body reputation property political office). Suffering arises from treating things not up to us as if they were. Freedom and equanimity arise from aligning desire and aversion exclusively with what is genuinely within our control.',
'The Stoic dichotomy of control is simultaneously ancient wisdom and a practical psychological tool of extraordinary power. Modern cognitive-behavioural therapy (CBT) is built on essentially the same insight: much psychological suffering arises from attempting to control what cannot be controlled while ignoring what can be cultivated. Epictetus, a former slave, developed this teaching under literal conditions of external powerlessness making his insight both autobiographically demonstrated and universally applicable.',
'Stoic philosophy Marcus Aurelius Rome ancient wisdom scroll',ARRAY['stoicism','epictetus','control','freedom','ethics']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',4,15,
'Platos Allegory of the Cave: after escaping to see the Sun (the Form of the Good) the philosophers obligation is to:',
'["Return to the cave and attempt to liberate the prisoners, even at the risk of death, because justice requires sharing true knowledge","Stay outside in the sunlight and contemplate the Forms, the cave requires no revisiting once the Good is perceived","Create a new city of philosophers outside the cave where escaped prisoners can live in truth","Record the nature of the Sun and the Forms in writing that cave-dwellers can eventually read"]',
0,'philosophical',
'In the Republic Plato describes the philosopher who escapes the cave as having an obligation to return. Having seen the Form of the Good the philosopher is more qualified than anyone to govern justly, but will appear foolish to those still watching shadows. The returning philosopher risks ridicule and potentially death (a clear allusion to Socrates). Yet justice, for Plato, requires this sacrifice.',
'The Caves politics are as radical as its metaphysics: Plato argues that the philosopher has an obligation to return to the imperfect world of politics not because it is pleasant but because justice demands it. The philosopher who refuses to govern will be governed by worse people. This is Platos answer to the Socratic question: given that the examined life is the best life what is that lifes responsibility to those who have not examined theirs? The answer: everything. The truth obligates.',
'Plato allegory cave philosophy shadows light Greece wisdom',ARRAY['plato','allegory cave','forms','philosopher king','justice']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',4,15,
'Viktor Frankls logotherapy proposes that the primary human motivation is:',
'["The search for meaning, and meaning can be found even in unavoidable suffering through the attitude one takes toward it","The will to pleasure, and suffering is always a sign of blocked or frustrated pleasure-seeking","The will to power, and suffering results from not having sufficient mastery over ones environment","The avoidance of death anxiety, and all human activity is ultimately motivated by terror management"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Frankl developed logotherapy based on his observation in Nazi concentration camps that those most likely to survive were not the physically strongest but those who had a reason to live, a purpose someone to return to a work to complete. The primary human motivation is the will to meaning and meaning can be found even in unavoidable suffering.',
'Frankls insight, that we cannot always choose our circumstances but can always choose our response to them, converges with both Stoic philosophy and Buddhist teachings on acceptance of dukkha. He who has a why to live can bear almost any how. The idea that meaning provides the psychological resources to endure anything has proven one of the most clinically effective ideas in all of psychotherapy.',
'Viktor Frankl meaning suffering philosophy psychology',ARRAY['frankl','logotherapy','meaning','will to meaning','suffering']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',12,50,
'Aristotles eudaimonia often translated as happiness more precisely means:',
'["Flourishing, living in accordance with ones highest faculties (reason and virtue) over a complete life, an activity not a feeling","Pleasurable sensory experience, the accumulation of positive feelings over a lifetime","Contentment and freedom from disturbance, the Aristotelian equivalent of Epicurean ataraxia","Success in achieving goals and earning community respect through accomplished deeds"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Eudaimonia (eu = good + daimon = spirit) is Aristotles term for the highest human good, activity of the soul in accordance with its highest virtue sustained over a complete life. Crucially eudaimonia is not a feeling but an activity, a way of living and functioning. A person living according to reason and virtue exercising capacities fully engaged in meaningful relationships and civic life is eudaimon regardless of momentary emotional state.',
'The distinction between eudaimonia and hedonia (pleasure/positive affect) describes two radically different visions of the good life. Hedonia is about how good one feels; eudaimonia is about how well one is functioning as a human being. Research in positive psychology has rediscovered this distinction empirically: the factors predicting long-term wellbeing (meaning engagement positive relationships accomplishment) do not always produce pleasurable feelings in the moment. Aristotle was right that the best life is not necessarily the most pleasant one.',
'Aristotle ancient philosophy Greece ethics virtue flourishing',ARRAY['aristotle','eudaimonia','flourishing','virtue','ethics']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',12,50,
'The Taoist concept of wu wei (non-action) teaches:',
'["Acting in alignment with the natural flow of reality rather than forcing, effortless action that achieves without struggle","Complete passivity and inaction, the sage does nothing because all action creates karma","The renunciation of all goals and desires, achievement is impossible without surrendering the desire to achieve","Acting only through the body not through the mind, all mental interference with natural impulse is wu weis opposite"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Wu wei does not mean inaction or laziness, it means action so naturally aligned with the Tao that it requires no force produces no resistance and leaves no trace. The metaphors used, water carving the Grand Canyon a skilled craftsman whose tool moves as if by itself the tree that bends in the storm and survives while the rigid tree breaks, all point to effortless effectiveness through perfect alignment with conditions.',
'Wu weis paradox is that the most effective action often feels like non-action, so perfectly aligned with conditions that it seems effortless. This maps onto the psychological experience of flow in which peak performance occurs precisely when the effortful self steps aside. The Taoist sage and the master athlete are engaged in the same fundamental discipline.',
'Tao Te Ching Taoist philosophy water flow nature wisdom',ARRAY['taoism','wu wei','non-action','effortless','flow']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',1,5,
'The Buddhist concept of karuna (compassion) is defined as:',
'["The wish for all beings to be free from suffering, combined with the motivation to actively relieve that suffering","Feeling pity or sympathy for those less fortunate than oneself, a passive emotional response","The recognition that all beings share the same fundamental nature, a philosophical rather than emotional insight","Unconditional love for all beings regardless of their actions, equivalent to the Christian concept of agape"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Karuna (Sanskrit/Pali: compassion) is specifically defined in Buddhism as the wish for all beings to be free from suffering, combined with the motivation to actively relieve that suffering. It is distinguished from pity (which looks down at others suffering from a distance) and from grief (which is overwhelmed by suffering). Karuna is the active engaged movement toward suffering in order to relieve it.',
'The Buddhist distinction between compassion and pity is psychologically precise and clinically important. Compassion (feeling with) maintains ones own stability while engaging with anothers pain. Pity (feeling sorry for) creates a hierarchy between the compassionate person and the suffering person. The Buddhist brahmaviharas training system is essentially a sophisticated programme for developing the psychological capacities needed to engage with suffering without being overwhelmed by it.',
'Buddhist meditation compassion lotus flowers peaceful temple',ARRAY['buddhism','karuna','compassion','brahmavihara','loving kindness']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',4,15,
'Marcus Aurelius wrote his Meditations as:',
'["Personal private reflections, notes to himself to maintain Stoic discipline and remember Stoic principles, never intended for publication","A philosophical treatise addressed to his son Commodus to guide his future rule as emperor","A public declaration of imperial ethics intended to set standards for the Roman senate and military","Letters to his teacher Epictetus working through the practical challenges of applying Stoic philosophy to imperial life"]',
0,'historical',
'The Meditations (literally To Himself in Greek) is a personal journal written in Greek by Roman Emperor Marcus Aurelius (161-180 CE), reminders to himself about Stoic principles and how to live them amid the distractions corruptions and temptations of imperial power. It was never intended for publication and contains many repetitions suggesting it was a genuine ongoing practice of philosophical self-examination rather than a composed literary work.',
'The Meditations is unique in world literature: a diary of psychological self-discipline written by the most powerful person in the world. Marcus was constantly returning to the same Stoic principles, duty service impermanence the unreality of external goods, because these principles were genuinely difficult to embody amid the temptations of absolute power. The text is a demonstration that wisdom is not achieved once but practiced continuously.',
'Marcus Aurelius Roman Emperor philosophy Stoic Meditations ancient',ARRAY['marcus aurelius','meditations','stoicism','roman emperor','philosophy']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',12,50,
'What is the central ethical teaching in Kants categorical imperative?',
'["Act only according to principles that you could will to be universal laws, moral duty determined by reason not consequences or feelings","Act to produce the greatest happiness for the greatest number of people, moral duty determined by beneficial consequences","Act as your highest character would act, moral duty determined by virtue and excellence of character","Act as the divine commands, moral duty determined by Gods revealed will interpreted through reason"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Kants categorical imperative (Groundwork for the Metaphysics of Morals 1785) has two key formulations: 1) Act only according to that maxim whereby you can at the same time will that it should become a universal law. 2) Act so that you treat humanity both in yourself and in others always as an end and never as a means only. This is an ethics based entirely on rational duty (deontology) rather than on consequences (consequentialism) or virtue (virtue ethics).',
'The categorical imperative is one of the most influential ethical frameworks in modern philosophy. Its strength: it provides a clear rational test for moral action (could this be universalised?) independent of self-interest or cultural convention. Its limitation: it can produce counterintuitive results in extreme cases (must you tell the truth to a murderer asking where your friend is hiding?). Kant versus consequentialism remains one of the central debates in contemporary ethics.',
'Kant categorical imperative ethics philosophy morality reason',ARRAY['kant','categorical imperative','deontology','ethics','moral philosophy']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',4,15,
'The Daoist parable of Cook Ding (Zhuangzi) illustrates the concept of wu wei through:',
'["A master butcher who cuts through an ox following its natural structure with such perfect skill that his blade never dulls, demonstrating mastery through alignment with nature rather than force","A cook who refuses to prepare meat because all living beings are sacred, demonstrating the compassion that arises from enlightened awareness of the unity of all life","A chef who creates perfect meals through pure spontaneous inspiration, demonstrating that thought and planning are obstacles to true creative mastery","A kitchen worker who finds the divine in the most mundane task, demonstrating that enlightenment can be found in ordinary work if approached with full attention"]',
0,'philosophical',
'The parable of Cook Ding in the Zhuangzi describes a butcher whose cleaver never dulls even after 19 years of use. His secret: he does not cut through the ox but follows its natural structure, finding the spaces between joints and ligaments and gliding through them. His technique requires no force because it works with the nature of the ox rather than against it. This is wu wei in action: mastery through perfect alignment with the natural order.',
'Cook Dings art represents the Taoist ideal of te (virtue power), the natural competence that arises when one is perfectly aligned with the Tao. Unlike the Western ideal of mastery through overcoming resistance and imposing ones will the Taoist master achieves by discovering and following the path of least resistance that is inherent in every situation. The perfect swordsman the perfect cook and the perfect ruler all operate on the same principle: follow the natural structure of things.',
'Tao Zhuangzi philosophy ancient Chinese wisdom parable',ARRAY['zhuangzi','cook ding','wu wei','taoism','mastery']);

